'}, {'created': '2017-02-01 16:54:29.000000000', 'message': 'Add API and conductor methods for [un]rescue

Adds API and Conductor methods to support rescue and unrescue.

After rescuing a node, it will be left running a rescue ramdisk,
configured with the rescue_password, and listening with ssh on the
specified network interfaces.

Unrescuing a node will return the node to Active.

This also adds the rescue_interface field to the Node object with
appropriate database migrations to allow for the use of rescue mode with
dynamic drivers.

This change raised the complexity of the provision method in the node
controller. I added a todo to the method to refactor it to be less
complex, and raised the permitted complexity in tox.ini.

Change-Id: I3953ff0b1ca000f8ae83fb7b3c663f848a149345

'}, {'created': '2017-05-17 10:56:12.000000000', 'message': 'Add API and conductor methods for [un]rescue

Adds API and Conductor methods to support rescue and unrescue.

After rescuing a node, it will be left running a rescue ramdisk,
configured with the rescue_password, and listening with ssh on the
specified network interfaces.

Unrescuing a node will return the node to Active.

This also adds the rescue_interface field to the Node object with
appropriate database migrations to allow for the use of rescue mode with
dynamic drivers.

This change raised the complexity of the provision method in the node
controller. I added a todo to the method to refactor it to be less
complex, and raised the permitted complexity in tox.ini.

Change-Id: I3953ff0b1ca000f8ae83fb7b3c663f848a149345
Partial-bug: #1526449
Co-Authored-By: Josh Gachnang <josh@pcsforeducation.com>

commit_message:
Add API methods for [un]rescue

Adds API methods to support rescue and unrescue.

After rescuing a node, it will be left running a rescue ramdisk,
configured with the rescue_password, and listening with ssh on the
specified network interfaces.

Unrescuing a node will return the node to Active.

Change-Id: I3953ff0b1ca000f8ae83fb7b3c663f848a149345
Partial-bug: #1526449
Co-Authored-By: Jay Faulkner <jay@jvf.cc>
Co-Authored-By: Josh Gachnang <josh@pcsforeducation.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jesse J. Cook <jesse.j.cook@member.fsf.org>
Co-Authored-By: Mario Villaplana <mario.villaplana@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Aparna <aparnavtce@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Shivanand Tendulker <stendulker@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Resolve unit test failures with going to oslo.serialization 2.3.0

openstack/oslo.serialization made a change in commit
c1a7079c26d27a2e46cca26963d3d9aa040bdbe8 which changed how
jsonutils.to_primitive() handles Exception objects. Previously the
actual Exception object would be returned but now it returns a 'repr'
of the object. This was done because CircularReferences were occuring
in some use cases with Exceptions and also in version 3.0 of
oslo.serialization they were going to raise a ValueError() for
unhandled types and this change caused Exceptions to now be handled.

The code previously would call the serialization function and if any
unknown Exception occurred it would just return action_result. With
the change to oslo.serialization an exception was no longer being
raised and thus no Exception would be raised and caught.

Now check if action_result is an Exception and if so return it.

Closes-Bug: #1728368
Change-Id: Ic374ec891a65f603433091cdae27b0d4aac8362f

commit_message:
Pass blacklisted_{ip_addresses,hostnames} to major_upgrade_steps

Durig upgrade PostDeploySteps is mapped into major_upgrade_steps
which was missing blacklisted_{ip_addresses,hostnames} previously
added only into deploy-steps.

Change-Id: Ifdcdad63e430972f7254f0c40e021b00333fdf56
Closes-Bug: 1745379

commit_message:
Add post_upgrade_tasks with post_upgrade_steps_playbook output

This wires up the post_upgrade_tasks tasks to be written as
ansible playbooks like the upgrade/update_tasks. This will
write out a post_upgrade_steps_playbook ansible playbook.

Used in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/489201/ by ODL
and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/505603/ cinder-volume
Q upgrade spec @ Ibde21e6efae3a7d311bee526d63c5692c4e27b28
Related Blueprint: major-upgrade-workflow

Change-Id: Ib6188c91076eabf20d6e358ca247fed802369a7f

commit_message:
Replace curly quotes with straight quotes

Curly quotes usually input from Chinese input method.
When read from english context, it makes some confusion.

Change-Id: I37f496630161991cd568e22dd7f54319c4f4f72d

commit_message:
Remove commas in setup.cfg package classifiers

This is likely causing an upload to pypi to fail with the following
error:

    Error: 'Development Status :: 3 - Alpha,' is not a valid choice for this field

Change-Id: Ieba2a4bec5ffc8e618501b38f73628e0b59c12a5

[{'created': '2017-10-10 00:37:56.000000000', 'message': 'Fix bulk heartbeating when emitting XML

Previously, we would set eventlet.minimum_write_chunk_size *after* we
emit the XML declaration. As a result, eventlet thinks it should buffer
the entire response, rendering our attempts at heartbeating useless.

Change-Id: Idb58c6cc982cc221fed5fc837afd06aa958d9ad4
'}]
commit_message:
Fix bulk heartbeating when emitting XML

Previously, we would set eventlet.minimum_write_chunk_size *after* we
emit the XML declaration. As a result, eventlet thinks it should buffer
the entire response, rendering our attempts at heartbeating useless.

Change-Id: Idb58c6cc982cc221fed5fc837afd06aa958d9ad4

commit_message:
Add rescue_interface to node and driver

Add support for rescue_interface to the commands below:

 * openstack baremetal node create
 * openstack baremetal node show
 * openstack baremetal node set
 * openstack baremetal node unset
 * openstack baremetal driver list
 * openstack baremetal driver show

Change-Id: Ib91d67a95092713add0d5025d8755f212c59f659

Tested Okay for me.
Without the patch (lb not deleted): http://paste.openstack.org/show/627822/
With the patch (lb deleted): http://paste.openstack.org/show/627826/

I simply tested by creating a neutron port in the security group assigned to the VIP port, so we'll fail to delete it.
 
A couple of comments:
1. I think it would be valuable to add a test for this here: https://github.com/openstack/octavia/blob/62c398c5cb2d9d59955fd43b86cf0a6797fdf1fe/octavia/network/drivers/neutron/allowed_address_pairs.py#L275
2. With your patch, the loadbalancer gets deleted (which is great) but because we cannot delete the security group, we also fail to deallocate the VIP port. Can we improve this even further so in a case where we cannot delete the security group we will at least delete the VIP port?

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 25239, 'date': '2017-11-30 14:19:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

That's really awesome Nir.

(1 comment)

This does indeed now succeed to delete the VIP port, despite the fact it fails to delete the security group. Good job there.
I think this change should be better reflected in the logs:

See this exception: http://paste.openstack.org/show/628028/

1. See my comment about the security group id.
2. For cases that we just fail to delete the security group, maybe we should have an exception with a more specific name (rather than DeallocateVIPException)
3. For some reason now, with your change it does not retry to delete the security group. Please look into that. this happens here: https://github.com/openstack/octavia/blob/bc5a1e9ef5bb6cc3245c350eb0b57974f5f96b7f/octavia/network/drivers/neutron/allowed_address_pairs.py#L218

I think this patch is really close to being finalized.'}, {'account_id': 25239, 'date': '2017-12-03 16:21:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Regarding comment No. 2: 2. My initial thinking was that it would be considered overkill to add an exception (e.g. removalVIPSecGroupExc) that is task-internal and forever silenced, where there's already an internal exception, and logging is quite informative as it is.
For the rest of the points: see my revised error handling.
It's not perfect, as currently the sec_group's UUID is printed twice in the same log line for the conflict scenario (allowed_address_pairs.py:L238), but I'd rather have it that way than adding more logic on the error handling block. I'm open to suggestions, though."}, {'account_id': 25239, 'date': '2017-12-03 16:30:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 25239, 'date': '2017-12-03 16:43:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2017-12-03 18:11:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Concur with @johnsom - In my daily adventures I am been called upon to clean up resources which are left behind - so the less we leave behind the better ;-) 

I also have seen us raising an error ro derail. bigger orchestration moves but I argue those tools should be more resilient and. not duke then they get one error.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2018-01-26 23:59:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

I would tend to agree as well -- leaving orphaned objects in a cloud is not good, especially if they actually tie up resources (in this case, IP address space / quotas). I'd rather see more retry logic in some places that currently fail outright, so we could attempt to actually get to a cleaner state more reliably. Otherwise, I'd like someone to really be forced to see that something went wrong and deal with it, rather than letting stuff silently fail until you realize half your IP space is gone and you don't know why."}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2018-01-27 01:11:00.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning per the discussion in the IRC channel and the user unable to abandon it on their own.'}]

commit_message:
Fail-proof VIP deallocation task

VIP's security_group might still be in-use during loadbalancer
deletion, and fail to clean-up. Prior to this patch, a failure
to delete the security group had resulted in failure to remove
the loadbalancer and its VIP.

This patch solves the scenario described above by:
* Suppressing Neutron's exceptions in case of failed sec_group removal.
* Suppressing exceptions entirely from DeallocateVIP task.

Task: 5945
Story: 2001374

Change-Id: I051e3184208c1ad1fb53f57fe6f1c537149337b1

commit_message:
Enable automatic restart of memcached, apache and mongodb

Prior to Newton, HA deployments had automatic restart of non-Openstack
services on controller nodes. From Newton onward, after we switched to
systemd for the vast majority of services, Openstack services are
configured for automatic restart, but memcached apache and mongodb
lack it.

Generate a drop-in file for the mentioned services, so they can
restart automatically in both HA and non-HA deployments.

This change is similar to the original review in master [1], but
it is implemented without puppet-systemd, because all stable versions
upstream (N, O, P) ship with an outdated puppet-systemd and one
impacted version downstream (N) doesn't even ship puppet-systemd.

[1] I8576db193b358cf804e8aaeb0e05b31c635ae5ba

Change-Id: I7658f539db55b7416a9931822cfe2102c3388123
Closes-Bug: #1741263

commit_message:
Allow getthelogs to fetch job logs from rdoproject

CI job logs from logs.rdoproject.org use another
console log name and there is no ending '/log' in the URLs.

It would be nice to be able to collect those logs for
tripleo CI jobs as well.

Change-Id: I137cd3eb749f24cb72bb675faca625a0f1f68000
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Update keystone v2/tokenauth example

It is no longer possible to authenticate with a service token, and
keystone v2 has been removed. Stop documenting it. Also correct
"secrete" misspelling that can cause some confusion to linguists.

Change-Id: Iac15360957f281643d20b5f3469ad56148e6d4f0

Add scope_types to trust policies

This change isolates trust operations to project-scoped tokens with
a FIXME inline to expand usage to system scope eventually.

Let's keep the domain configuration API as a system administrator API
until we evolve the policy checks in code to handle project and
domain administrators.

commit_message:
Add scope_types to service provider policies

Since setting up federation requires configuration changes, it makes
sense to set the scope_types for service provider policies to
`system`.

From now on, a warning will be logged when a project-scoped token is
used to manage service providers. Operators will have the option to
require system-scoped tokens for these policies by enabling the
`enforce_scope` option via oslo.policy's configuration.

Change-Id: I0c4f5a2ba30b955e89ac0845e858ac6d845b25d8

commit_message:
iRMC:Support preparing rescue ramdisk in iRMC PXE

Adds support to prepare rescue ramdisk to iRMC PXE boot interface,
which is a subclass of PXE boot interface by adding the new argument.

Also adds unit tests to confirm iRMC PXE boot interface passes the
same tests as generic PXE boot interface.

Change-Id: I1b4aeb207772a09cacf0bff910be4061ec5c74ee
Related-Bug: #1526449

[{'created': '2018-01-26 16:01:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fix unit tests for UEFI iSCSI boot for ILO

https://review.openstack.org/468288 added some unit tests for the
UEFI iSCSI boot for ILO, which fail when proliantutils is installed
in the virtualenv (it was not in the gate).

The reason for this is that they do not pass a value to the constructor
of ilo_error.IloError and ilo_error.IloCommandNotSupportedInBiosError,
which makes the unit tests fail, as seen when the package was built
in RDO [1].

This patch adds the required value, as used by other unit tests.

[1] - https://trunk.rdoproject.org/centos7/73/71/737147706405785b3879135872d6efb2953a9aea_0520bb51

Change-Id: I50d919047ddb9edf1a1ae1a994a8f71e420718d9
'}]
commit_message:
Fix unit tests for UEFI iSCSI boot for ILO

https://review.openstack.org/468288 added some unit tests for the
UEFI iSCSI boot for ILO, which fail when proliantutils is installed
in the virtualenv (it was not in the gate).

The reason for this is that they do not pass a value to the constructor
of ilo_error.IloError and ilo_error.IloCommandNotSupportedInBiosError,
which makes the unit tests fail, as seen when the package was built
in RDO [1].

This patch adds the required value, as used by other unit tests.

[1] - https://trunk.rdoproject.org/centos7/73/71/737147706405785b3879135872d6efb2953a9aea_0520bb51

Change-Id: I50d919047ddb9edf1a1ae1a994a8f71e420718d9

commit_message:
Add scope_types for revoke event policies

This commit associates `system` to revoke event policies, since these
policies were developed to assist the system in offline token
validation.

From now on, a warning will be logged when a project-scoped token is
used to get revocation events. Operators can opt into requiring
system-scoped tokens for these policies by enabling oslo.policy's
`enforce_scope` configuration option, which will result in an
HTTP Forbidden exception when mismatching scope is used.

Change-Id: I1dddeb216b2523b8471e5f2d5370921bb7a45e7f

[{'created': '2018-01-02 18:54:41.000000000', 'message': 'Only call numa_fit_instance_to_host if necessary

The numa_fit_instance_to_host method emits a debug message
when there is no provided host or instance topology:

  "Require both a host and instance NUMA topology to fit instance on host"

This can be confused with something that is wrong when most of the
time it just means the request spec doesn't have a NUMA topology
requirement.

This change avoids calling the method altogether if there is no
host and instance topology, just like in the NUMATopologyFilter.

Change-Id: Iba0f616927dc44929df07a19f8f33d4cc07017d1
'}]
commit_message:
Only call numa_fit_instance_to_host if necessary

The numa_fit_instance_to_host method emits a debug message
when there is no provided host or instance topology:

  "Require both a host and instance NUMA topology to fit instance on host"

This can be confused with something that is wrong when most of the
time it just means the request spec doesn't have a NUMA topology
requirement.

This change avoids calling the method altogether if there is no
host and instance topology, just like in the NUMATopologyFilter.

Change-Id: Iba0f616927dc44929df07a19f8f33d4cc07017d1

[{'created': '2017-10-06 17:30:30.000000000', 'message': 'Deprecate allowed_direct_url_schemes and nova.image.download.modules

The only in-tree implementation of the nova.image.download.modules
extension point was nova.image.download.file which was removed in
Pike: I7687cc89545a7a8b295dd6535b4ccebc913a2e0e

At the time of that removal, there was an operators ML thread
asking if anyone was using this code, or the extension point,
and the answer was no (or no answer at all).

Since we have no in-tree implementation of this extension point
and the extension point itself is not maintained or documented,
and even the TransferBase base class was removed in Pike, we
should deprecate the extension point and the configuration option
associated with its use so that we can simplify our internal
glance API client code.

Note that the libvirt Rbd image backend which does support
direct_url / image locations configuration for fast clones is
still supported and unrelated to this code.

Change-Id: I13162ebc9050dd2c468d0f8b969b96409f60afa8
'}]
commit_message:
Deprecate allowed_direct_url_schemes and nova.image.download.modules

The only in-tree implementation of the nova.image.download.modules
extension point was nova.image.download.file which was removed in
Pike: I7687cc89545a7a8b295dd6535b4ccebc913a2e0e

At the time of that removal, there was an operators ML thread
asking if anyone was using this code, or the extension point,
and the answer was no (or no answer at all).

Since we have no in-tree implementation of this extension point
and the extension point itself is not maintained or documented,
and even the TransferBase base class was removed in Pike, we
should deprecate the extension point and the configuration option
associated with its use so that we can simplify our internal
glance API client code.

Note that the libvirt Rbd image backend which does support
direct_url / image locations configuration for fast clones is
still supported and unrelated to this code.

Change-Id: I13162ebc9050dd2c468d0f8b969b96409f60afa8

commit_message:
Sanitize validations output

Ensure the output module methods call _dump_results() in order to

[{'created': '2018-01-25 21:24:38.000000000', 'message': 'Handle TZ change in iso8601 >=0.1.12

The iso8601 lib introduced a change such that if running on python
3.2 or later it internally uses the python timezone information
instead of its own implementation. This does not change direct
date handling, but when converting this value there is a slight
difference where now python 2.x will show UTC times as "UTC", but
on python 3 they will end up with "UTC+00:00".

The to_primitive call for DateTime fields was doing an exact match
on "UTC" to determine whether to include "Z" in the resulting string.
This updates that handling to recognize either of the new values.

commit_message:
Handle TZ change in iso8601 >=0.1.12

The iso8601 lib introduced a change such that if running on python
3.2 or later it internally uses the python timezone information
instead of its own implementation. This does not change direct
date handling, but when converting this value there is a slight
difference where now python 2.x will show UTC times as "UTC", but
on python 3 they will end up with "UTC+00:00".

The to_primitive call for DateTime fields was doing an exact match
on "UTC" to determine whether to include "Z" in the resulting string.
This updates that handling to recognize either of the new values.

Change-Id: Iff2e5a5b056605fae59f2489cc7baa1fc2e3352f
Closes-bug: #1744160
(cherry picked from commit 9c4aefb8ea88fd5505602c95f4762fdeb3aea183)
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>

commit_message:
Add a parameter to be able to override clients_keystone/auth_uri.

It is usually the same as auth_url which is defined there
$::heat::keystone::authtoken::auth_url.  We can now point this to
another part of the catalog (ie, public vs internal for instance).

Co-Authored-By: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovat@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I4429d86d831f49f1bc0fef04379a81ada20b6ab6
(cherry picked from commit 7870a0f8ff78fddb0990889c91988a3b08a6f221)

commit_message:
[cleanup] Fix identifiers for Mistral resources

Rally cleanup supports 3 Mistral resources: workbooks, workflows and
executions.

The min version of supported python-mistralclient (3.1.0 from our
requirements.txt) represents all these resources via special classes
[1][2][3] which have one parent class [4].

Issues with current rally cleanup code:

- Despite the fact that raw mistral objects do not support __getitem__
  method, `id` and `name` fields are tried to be accessed in such way,
  which made cleanup those resources broken for a long time (from the
  beggining?!)
- Mistral executions do not have own name, which we can use for
  filtering, but it stores workflow name, even if it was removed.
  Workflow name can be and should be used as an identifier.

Why these issues were not detected before:

- The Rally task which we used in CI has `do_delete=true` option for all
  workloads which makes workload to delete resources by itself without
  waiting for global cleanup.

  The fix is provided in this patch

- Despite the fact that osresources includes mistral resources to check
  that nothing is left after task execution, it doesn't help since there
  is no `all-tenants` option which turns listing resources from admin
  tenant to listing all existing resources.

  Cannot be fixed via our code.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/python-mistralclient/blob/3.1.0/mistralclient/api/v2/workbooks.py#L20
[2] https://github.com/openstack/python-mistralclient/blob/3.1.0/mistralclient/api/v2/workflows.py#L25
[3] https://github.com/openstack/python-mistralclient/blob/3.1.0/mistralclient/api/v2/executions.py#L27
[4] https://github.com/openstack/python-mistralclient/blob/3.1.0/mistralclient/api/base.py#L19

Change-Id: I57fa05ff26aa0836224ba7a3393833ba31fe58dd

commit_message:
Add scope_types to group policies

By default, groups have always required system or cloud
administrators authorization. This commit adds 'system' to all group
policies with a FIXME in the event we want to open those APIs up to
project or domain administrators.

Change-Id: Icf6575e4e67f0bd72b87faf06acde1a00b3bc244

'}, {'created': '2018-01-23 16:03:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add scope_types to grant policies

Since grants can exist on either the system or a project, it makes
sense to have them associated to both `system` and `project` scopes.
But until we have logic in keystone that can enforce those checks, we
keep the scope_types set to `system`. This ensures backwards
compatibility and helps resolve admin-ness issues until we get to
that point.

Change-Id: I310c88bae7986e3163408f621e266f96fd255edc
'}]
commit_message:
Add scope_types to grant policies

Since grants can exist on either the system or a project, it makes
sense to have them associated to both `system` and `project` scopes.
But until we have logic in keystone that can enforce those checks, we
keep the scope_types set to `system`. This ensures backwards
compatibility and helps resolve admin-ness issues until we get to
that point.

Change-Id: I310c88bae7986e3163408f621e266f96fd255edc

commit_message:
functional test fix: ignore more tables in DB consistency check

Our current logic for ignoring DBs that which shouldn't
check in the DB/model consistency check is:
- incomplete (missing new bagpipe tables), causing
  functional test to break [1]
- not flexible enough

Such issues have arised in the past with ODL tables.

This change makes the mecanism more flexible, removing
the need to list explicit table names, and allowing wildcarding.

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/16/537816/1/check/legacy-networking-bgpvpn-dsvm-functional/01973b2/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-01-26_09_26_39_360246

Change-Id: I0c79536ae2f802a5408e9656a5026147f6730211

commit_message:
Less opinionated detection of service env files

This should support OOOQ while hopefully not damaging Infrared
integration. We need to specifically look for the env files that match
the patterns we want, and we also need to support multiple env files
on a single line, because that's how OOOQ passes them in.

This solution should work both for the transformed and untransformed
deployment commands.

Closes-Bug: 1745593
Co-Authored-By: Jose Luis Franco <jfrancoa@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I4164ef552c333d6b9672c1a3d55c15a1b76e7bb7
(cherry picked from commit 35fdef283aa90e9543ed37cb657394f6516e3777)

commit_message:
More robust check for deployment_with_ha

The current check of "-pacemaker" being present in deployment command
is not sufficient for OOOQ based environments (and CI). Checking the
EnabledServices stack output should be somewhat more robust. We only
want deployment_with_ha if the deployment was with
pacemaker (pacemaker_present test) and we can't assume pacemaker is
the default (is_upstream test).

Closes-Bug: #1745593
Co-Authored-By: Jose Luis Franco <jfrancoa@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I8b0ff3797d8f6d697086701c80e1ae159cff2bf4
(cherry picked from commit bea01b1dad636d91e278d3fd52fb978b2ebb5e22)

commit_message:
Document scope_types for ec2 policies

The ec2 poicies are tricky because they require keystone to be
smarter about the scope of the token used when accessing those
APIs. Until keystone supports those policy checks in code, we
will leave these commented and track the work in a bug.

Change-Id: I180cd5425144e4410857f3f7811568502cd57abf

commit_message:
Improve netenv validation and add IPv6 tests

This patch improves the network environment validation to work with very
large IP ranges (when using IPv6).

Prior to this patch the validation would check for every IP within an IP
ranges to see if it was inside (valid) or outside (invalid) of a subnet.
This isn't feasible for many IPv6 cases when IP ranges can be very
large. Instead of comparing each IP this patch checks the
netaddr.IPRange object as a whole against the subnet.

Change-Id: Icbd2e6483c991835d62429d06b5745742186b5c5

The pip command was not installed.  Added a couple of

[{'created': '2018-01-25 17:06:32.000000000', 'message': "Use the 'ironic' queue for the gate

When doing the 'gate' build have the ironic-python-agent jobs be part
of the 'ironic' queue. More information on this is in [1]. The benefit
of this is that we are only impacted by ironic projects if we do this.

From [1]:
Pipelines which use the dependent pipeline manager maintain separate
queues for groups of projects. When Zuul serializes a set of changes
which represent future potential project states, it must know about
all of the projects within Zuul which may have an effect on the
outcome of the jobs it runs. If project A uses project B as a library,
then Zuul must be told about that relationship so that it knows to
serialize changes to A and B together, so that it does not merge a
change to B while it is testing a change to A.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/infra/zuul/feature/zuulv3/user/config.html

Change-Id: Ib0476fb36196d77c431043ea6a48dc842f8d3a65

commit_message:
Use the 'ironic' queue for the gate

When doing the 'gate' build have the ironic-python-agent jobs be part
of the 'ironic' queue. More information on this is in [1]. The benefit
of this is that we are only impacted by ironic projects if we do this.

From [1]:
Pipelines which use the dependent pipeline manager maintain separate
queues for groups of projects. When Zuul serializes a set of changes
which represent future potential project states, it must know about
all of the projects within Zuul which may have an effect on the
outcome of the jobs it runs. If project A uses project B as a library,
then Zuul must be told about that relationship so that it knows to
serialize changes to A and B together, so that it does not merge a
change to B while it is testing a change to A.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/infra/zuul/feature/zuulv3/user/config.html

Change-Id: Ib0476fb36196d77c431043ea6a48dc842f8d3a65

commit_message:
Fix nested template genearation when attribute path is not string

When determining attributes to cache, we seem to be assuming the
paths to be strings. If there are resource references in outputs
it would be None during validation.

As we've the same code snippet in all group resources
ex. ResourceGroup, ResourceChain and heat AutoScalingGroup, this
fixes it in all those places.

Change-Id: I36d623b183d01632041113f7bff63bf255f5d53c
Closes-Bug: #1719603
(cherry picked from commit aabb3392b30e4905e8b780bec4c819ec6058b2b6)

commit_message:
Add metadata version openstack/2015-10-15

This version introduced the network_data.json file, and is supported by
cloud-init 0.7.9. Cloud-init 0.7.9 will always prefer a versioned
metadata to 'latest', which in this case forces the use of the
2012-08-10 Folsom version, which does not provide network_data.json.

Change-Id: I3a604c170e124de3bbbe95f002d14439c138ca3e
Closes-Bug: #1742957

commit_message:
Remove default_bind_mount_logs from config changes.

Changing the value for default_bind_mount_logs on upgrade will make all
container restart. It only make sense to add this to the config when:
- you upgrade to the release that changes the default behavior
    - this is to keep the old default.
- The setting is not set in the configuration.
    - If the config is present, you don't want to change it.

Change-Id: I37217352357dee8c844d3b20d28075f7e4ef1223
Related-Bug: #1745212

then Zuul must be told about that relationship so that it knows to
serialize changes to A and B together, so that it does not merge a
change to B while it is testing a change to A.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/infra/zuul/feature/zuulv3/user/config.html

Change-Id: Ib353d00efb590afc883521eebd3b1fc45398b09f

commit_message:
Fix logic to check for insecure Keystone

The logic to check for insecure Keystone would only validate if
both HAproxy and Keystone SSL is installed.  However, in the case
where SSL happens at either of those (ex. SSL at HAproxy only),
then it would still declare it as insecure (it is not however
as we're hitting the VIP which does SSL termination).

This changes the behaviour to check if the protocol is HTTPs and
either the Keystone or HAproxy certificates are defined then it
considers it as secure, otherwise it is insecure.

Closes-Bug: #1745479
Co-Authored-By: Logan V <logan2211@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I3683c5d50cab2d321337c71bed565d2e2ab861fc

commit_message:
Allow to increase docker daemon verbosity

This patch exposes puppet_tripleo's docker_options
in the tripleo-heat-templates.

Change-Id: I1b48b2a25dfa5afc3d2e4e4c8f0593e03ead3907
Closes-bug: #1715134
(cherry picked from commit 5ef76cc16c4a4b5e0dce69456dac7ae98fd7af6a)

device as just a sysfs file) that mediated devices are not persisted.

That change will iterate over all the instances, see if they have a nested

commit_message:
Recreate mediated devices on reboot

There is a lacking feature in libvirt (due to the nature of what is mediated
device as just a sysfs file) that mediated devices are not persisted.
When you reboot your host, you loose all of them which can be a big pain for
operators having allocated guests using vGPUs.

This change will iterate over all the instances, see if they have a nested
vGPU, check if the related mediated device exists, and if not, rebalance
between physical GPUs to find a proper one which can fit.

Note that due to the fact we don't persist neither in Nova the mediated device
information, mediated devices can be created on different physical devices that
they were before the reboot. That's not a big deal since we only support one
type at the moment, but that could become a problem later as we would need to
figure out which type the mediated device was before the reboot.

Partially-Implements: blueprint add-support-for-vgpu
Change-Id: Ie6c9108808a461359d717d8a9e9399c8a407bfe9

commit_message:
New configuration being added for Cisco UCSM ML2 driver

Cisco UCSM ML2 driver now accepts the following new configuration
parameters:
1. ucsm_https_verify
2. sp_template_list

commit_message:
Fix pip install failure

At install_data hook, it tries to glance-image-import.conf which
does not exist. Since it is an optional file, let's not install it
by default.

Change-Id:  I8a5122355da43c592b0cbad0eb7921875e0a5e99

commit_message:
Add scope_types to identity provider policies

I set the policies for these to be `system` even though it makes
sense to have them be `system` and `project` scopes once it is
possible to add federated identity without having to roll apache
configuration files.

From now on, a warning will be logged when a project-scoped token is
used to manage identity providers. Operator will have the option to
enforce scope checking if they enable `enforce_scope` via
oslo.policy's configuration.

Change-Id: I2aa2ff866e1622d8dc2ce813956ac869be792b5f

commit_message:
Add scope_types to protocol policies

This commit sets scope type for all protocol policies to `system`.
Until keystone has support for setting up federated identity without
having to modify system configuration files, it doesn't make sense to
expose this functionality to project administrators who don't have
access to system configuration files.

From now on, a warning will be logged when a project-scoped token is
used to manage protocols. Operators can opt into requiring
system-scoped tokens for these policies by enabling oslo.policy's
`enforce_scope` configuration option, which will result in an HTTP
Forbidden exception when mismatching scope is detected.

Change-Id: I6b4f8c37cd5c103d79b34eab54d95901c07ec784

I'm not sure that we should be defining to many of our own variables for this, I kinda think our plugin should just adapt based on the local.conf configuration options that already exist for configuring Neutron in devstack. Otherwise I think we'll be duplicating a lot of the options E.g.

OVS_PHYSICAL_BRIDGE={bridge name}
PHYSICAL_NETWORK={network name}
PROVIDER_NETWORK_TYPE="flat"
PUBLIC_INTERFACE={network interface}'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2016-07-04 22:17:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Vasyl, thanks for the patch that we can support FLAT settings, just left nits inline.'}, {'account_id': 14525, 'date': '2016-07-05 07:29:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 14525, 'date': '2016-07-05 07:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(7 comments)

Haomeng, John, Sam thanks for review.

@Sam: >I'm not sure that we should be defining to many of our own   >variables for this, I kinda think our plugin should just adapt based >on the local.conf configuration options that already exist for >configuring Neutron in devstack. Otherwise I think we'll be >duplicating a lot of the options E.g.
>OVS_PHYSICAL_BRIDGE={bridge name}
>PHYSICAL_NETWORK={network name}
>PROVIDER_NETWORK_TYPE="flat"
>PUBLIC_INTERFACE={network interface}

I thought about it, but not sure that it is a right way since. It is possible to have any number of flat networks as you want, while Neutron devstack's plugin allows to configure only single flat.
Public network and Ironic may and should leave separately from each other, while if we using Neutron variables we just replace public by Ironic's flat which is not right way I think.
Furthermore we still need to create dummy interface if it doesn't exists.

I would like to see high level of abstraction in Neutron devstack plugin like: add_ml2_flat_network() - that defines logic to add an additional flat network without replacing existed flat networks.
We can elaborate when neutron is completely moved to devstack plugin.'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2016-07-05 07:49:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1

Thanks Vasyl for the update.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-07-05 09:13:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

[{'created': '2016-06-27 09:59:27.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Use FLAT network

This patch allows to setup FLAT Neutron network, and use
it by Ironic instances.
The patch introduce new variables with default values:
 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSYCAL_NETWORK: neutron physycal network name.
 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSYCAL_BRIDGE: physycal bridge name.
 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSYCAL_INTERFACE: interface name to map with flat
    network. If doesn't exist dummy interface is used.
 IRONIC_FLAT_SUBNET: ironic flat subnet
 IRONIC_FLAT_GATEWAY ironic flat subnet gateway. This address is
   assigned to $IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSYCAL_BRIDGE
 IRONIC_FLAT_NETWORK_NAME: neutron flat network name
 IRONIC_USE_FLAT_NETWORK: is a trigger to specify if flat network
  should be configured. If set to True, VMs is plugged to flat
  network.

Change-Id: Iff1d180cde81e874a4c26dd786cb42499ccf4f3b

 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSYCAL_NETWORK: neutron physycal network name.
 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSYCAL_INTERFACE: interface name to map with flat
    network. If doesn't exist dummy interface is used.
 IRONIC_FLAT_SUBNET: ironic flat subnet
 IRONIC_FLAT_GATEWAY ironic flat subnet gateway. This address is
   assigned to $IRONIC_VM_NETWORK_BRIDGE interface.
 IRONIC_FLAT_NETWORK_NAME: neutron flat network name

  should be configured. If set to True, VMs are plugged to flat
  network. And tempest will use this network to boot nova instances.

commit_message:
Allow to use FLAT network setup

This patch allows to setup FLAT Neutron network, and use
it by Ironic instances.

The patch introduce new variables:
 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSICAL_NETWORK: Neutron physycal network name.

 IRONIC_FLAT_PHYSICAL_INTERFACE: interface name to map with flat
   network. If doesn't exist dummy interface is used.

 IRONIC_FLAT_SUBNET: Ironic flat subnet

 IRONIC_FLAT_INTERFACE_IP this address is assigned to
   $IRONIC_VM_NETWORK_BRIDGE interface.

 IRONIC_FLAT_NETWORK_NAME: Neutron flat network name.

 IRONIC_NETWORK_INTERFACE: is a trigger to specify if flat network
   should be configured. If set to "flat", VMs are plugged to flat
   network. And tempest will use this network to boot nova instances.
   In case cleaning is enabled cleaning network is configured to
   Ironic flat network UUID if flat network is used.

Change-Id: Iff1d180cde81e874a4c26dd786cb42499ccf4f3b

commit_message:
include governed projects in output

In 0ba83e5 we started trying to ignore unofficial projects and
introduced a bug so that all projects were dropped from the project
list as part of that evaluation. This patch fixes the bug by copying
the valid data from the raw values read in to the list of values being
passed to the template.

Change-Id: I4aeafe6d8116f3b032a5d339660878a76a10e2f3
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Disable clear containers by default

ENABLE_CLEAR_CONTAINER should be set to false by default as they're
relying on third party repos which could break devstack installation at
some point.

[{'created': '2017-07-24 16:04:31.000000000', 'message': 'cinder incremental backup with ceph fails if last one deleted

If the last incremental backup is deleted then the backup snapshot
is deleted but the source volume snapshot remains. Due to mismatch
between the source volume snapshot and backup snapshot, there is an
error when "rbd export-diff" and "rbd import-diff" is done. Hence,
full backup happens.

To fix this issue, all the previous source volume snapshots are
preserved. When the last incremental backup is deleted, then its
backup snapshot is deleted. But because all the source volume snaps
exist, thus it can now update --from-snap for "rbd export-diff" to
be the most recent source volume snapshot for which there exists a
backup snapshot as well. This is how the incremental backup operation
will go successful.

For a user who upgrades to the new code, if the last backup snapshot
and source volume snapshot are in sync, i.e. both of them exist, then
the next create backup operation will continue as an incremental one.
However, if there is no source volume snapshot for the last existing
incremental backup (before the code was upgraded), then a full backup
happens. After this full backup, all the next backups are incremental
while all their corresponding source volume snapshots are also preserved.
In this way, after a user upgrades, if he deletes the last incremental
backup, the next create backup operation will be successful and be
incremental.

Since all the backup snapshots exist for all the backups, if the user
wants to restore a backup, which was created before the code was upgraded,
the user will not lose any data since the same base backup is used.

Change-Id: Ia9c29bb720152d42bec273202fa49ca4b6a41ce2
Closes-Bug: #1703011

commit_message:
cinder incremental backup with ceph fails if last one deleted

If the last incremental backup is deleted then the backup snapshot
is deleted but the source volume snapshot remains. Due to mismatch
between the source volume snapshot and backup snapshot, there is an
error when "rbd export-diff" and "rbd import-diff" is done. Hence,
full backup happens.

To fix this issue, all the previous source volume snapshots are
preserved. When the last incremental backup is deleted, then its
backup snapshot is deleted. But because all the source volume snaps
exist, thus it can now update --from-snap for "rbd export-diff" to
be the most recent source volume snapshot for which there exists a
backup snapshot as well. This is how the incremental backup operation
will go successful.

For a user who upgrades to the new code, if the last backup snapshot
and source volume snapshot are in sync, i.e. both of them exist, then
the next create backup operation will continue as an incremental one.
However, if there is no source volume snapshot for the last existing
incremental backup (before the code was upgraded), then a full backup
happens. After this full backup, all the next backups are incremental
while all their corresponding source volume snapshots are also preserved.
In this way, after a user upgrades, if he deletes the last incremental
backup, the next create backup operation will be successful and be
incremental.

Since all the backup snapshots exist for all the backups, if the user
wants to restore a backup, which was created before the code was upgraded,
the user will not lose any data since the same base backup is used.

Change-Id: Ia9c29bb720152d42bec273202fa49ca4b6a41ce2
Closes-Bug: #1703011

[{'created': '2018-01-23 19:18:38.000000000', 'message': 'Fix missing parentid on rule delete journal record

This fixes an error raised when deleting a security group if there are
pending rules to be deleted of that group as records in the journal
that were not triggered by the group deletion operation itself so that
they did not have the parent security group id as data of the record.

This happens when the rule and the group are deleted independently but
in rapid succession. It does not happen when the rules are deleted as a
consequence of deleting the group since the parentid is correctly set
in that case, neither when the group is deleted some time after the
rules when their records might have already been processed and removed.

This problem was encountered in OPNFV functest environment but may also
fix https://jira.opendaylight.org/browse/NETVIRT-896 and complement
change #533706.

commit_message:
Fix missing parentid on rule delete journal record

This fixes an error raised when deleting a security group if there are
pending rules to be deleted of that group as records in the journal
that were not triggered by the group deletion operation itself so that
they did not have the parent security group id as data of the record.

This happens when the rule and the group are deleted independently but
in rapid succession. It does not happen when the rules are deleted as a
consequence of deleting the group since the parentid is correctly set
in that case, neither when the group is deleted some time after the
rules when their records might have already been processed and removed.

This problem was encountered in OPNFV functest environment but may also
fix https://jira.opendaylight.org/browse/NETVIRT-896 and complement
change #533706.

Change-Id: I5ccdbdea9d803334c8ae9416b40e3c4b48a8144b
Closes-Bug: 1744966
Signed-off-by: Jaime Caamao Ruiz <jcaamano@suse.com>

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2017-11-15 15:50:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2017-11-15 15:57:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2017-11-17 09:34:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-11-17 16:30:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I'm a little less enthusiastic about this than I am for the similar changes that update the commands for building the docs. I agree with the idea of standardizing on stestr. I don't know how prescriptive we want to be about not allowing wrapper scripts or other changes that change the user experience when running the tests locally.

Have we seen issues with the way stestr is actually being used?"}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2017-11-17 18:23:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

stestr usage is pretty new (being used for projects for only a few months) but we can already see the problems wrapper scripts cause between projects using ostestr (which is just a wrapper script for stestr now) and straight stestr.

Here's a perfect example today checkout nova from master try to run 1 unit test and then try to do it on ironic and heat. You'll find that all 3 will be different. The cli is different for ironic requiring a cli arg like --regex before the test_id (ie: `tox -epy27 -- --regex $test_id`) because it is using ostestr. While the cli is the same for nova and heat, (just `tox -epy27 $test_id`) the output formatting is completely different, since heat is using testr's setuptools entrypoint. It also means that all the other options to the test runner are different between heat and nova. Also note the heat arguments won't be the same as any project using PBR's entrypoint or testr by itself, despite all using testr...

There is also the case of the single quotes around the posargs in the tox.ini, which may or may not require the use of -- on the cli to pass in an argument depending on whether it's quoted or not. Which is a potential difference between projects' tox.ini files. For example, this was something I spent a bunch of time on with nova because having 'tox -epy27 $regex' and not 'tox -epy27 -- $regex' work was critically important to them. (you can look at the git log on nova's tox.ini for how specific it was)

If we allow/encourage using wrapper scripts when a user starts interacting with tox to run tests they'll have to understand all of the differences and nuances between all of the test runners. That includes whatever the wrapper script is doing internally as well as how it's UX is different from the test runner they're used to on their project. This is something we saw all the time with testr, for example a recent bug (but hardly a unique one): https://github.com/testing-cabal/testrepository/issues/31 All wrapper scripts do is obfuscate how things are working form users.

In the short term in seems like a convenient way to workaround a problem, but eventually all it does cause is more confusion. Personally I'm guilty of falling into this trap in the past, having written 2 of the 4 testr wrappers I listed in the commit message. The idea here is to start to actually get everything working the same way through tox for all projects."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2017-11-17 21:31:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I am in favor of standardizing this, as I have also run into the 'how do I run one test?' problem across projects.

Between ostestr/stestr and zuulv3 I have been able to reduce the need for wrapper scripts in OSC to just variants of a single case for functional tests.  The wrapper is required to inject the required environment variables for the functional tests, there are no differences leaked up to the command line.

The CLI differences being leaked is the most noticeable issue for wrappers, I would be willing to narrow the wrapper ban to not making user-visible changes."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2017-11-18 05:36:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Dean ping me on IRC next week, I don't want to dive into it here. But, I took a look at the functional wrapper script in osc and I feel like that's something we can do natively in tox somehow (either through an extra command before the test runner or something else) But, it does raise a question of maybe having a follow up patch to have some standard definitions on how to handle functional job definitions in tox that require devstack.

My concern with wrapper scripts is twofold the user facing thing you mentioned, but also hiding the details of how things work. Besides things like the testr bug I linked to before there have been times I've seen weird unexpected issues mask themselves because of stuff happening inside things like the pretty_tox scripts that no one was expecting. For example cli args that silently ignored passed args and gave no indications, or typos that always cause a return code of 0.

I realize that every test suite is going to have different setup steps that are unique. But, what I'd like to see would be to have all of that be defined in the top level inside the tox job definitions so it's explicitly defined in one place. So if someone random needs to debug an issue it's all right there in the job definition instead of hidden in a lower level script or config file somewhere else."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-11-27 13:22:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1

There will probably be some hiccups as people adapt to this, but I think moving towards something unified and explicit is the right way to go.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2017-11-29 17:51:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-11-29 19:01:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I would like to see some more community input on this one. The test runner is one of the main interfaces developers have for interacting with code and "usability" is often subjective.'}, {'account_id': 17068, 'date': '2017-12-04 14:13:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

While I am not a stestr person, I like the fact we are standardizing in a clear/clean way.'}, {'account_id': 10459, 'date': '2017-12-05 14:59:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

cargo_cult-- custom_scripts-- working_standards++'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2018-01-07 14:28:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1

Yes, please let's find ways to standardize. I'm not in favor of bludgeoning projects with rules, but if there are ways they need to set up testing which can't be accomplished through the standard specified here it at least gives us a clear place to evolve such a standard so the next project with the same unusual need can also have guidance on how to solve it consistently."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2018-01-09 22:40:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2018-01-10 00:01:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 935, 'date': '2018-01-12 10:54:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2018-01-16 17:06:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I doubt there are many teams that doing it differently because they feel they are unique snowflakes. More likely they just all cargo-culted it from different places at different times. If there's one standard, documented way to do it, that's good for (almost) everyone."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2018-01-16 19:01:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I guess since Heat already adopted this recommendation (Ifaf3991e1c9400683e9c98185b86cb39ac3d318d) I should try it and leave some specific ergonomic feedback from the perspective of a testr/setuptools user:

* Running a subset of the tests using `tox -epy27 <regex>` worked the same
* Re-running failing tests using `tox -epy27 -- --failing` worked the same
* I wish I had known about the --no-discover option years ago. Honestly this is what I want instead of a regex 100% of the time. Discovery is slooooow.
* It reports failure data (stack trace, logs) as soon as a test fails so I can get to work debugging immediately instead of like 6 minutes later. This is a huge improvement over ostestr.
* The 6500 lines of scrollback (the reason I previously reverted os-testr from Heat) is still infuriating and makes me want to throw my computer out of a window.
* The --quiet option does nothing AFAICT.
* Adding the --no-subunit-trace option *after* the 'run' subcommand gets rid of the excess output. I submitted a patch to do that in Heat (I9fe8cc6a540c48d7fc04cef5e65e87dc3cce52fe), and I'd suggest including it in the recommendation here.
* It's confusing that unknown options are silently ignored (https://github.com/mtreinish/stestr/issues/99), especially when some options have to go before and some after the subcommand."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2018-01-16 20:13:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> I guess since Heat already adopted this recommendation
 > (Ifaf3991e1c9400683e9c98185b86cb39ac3d318d) I should try it and
 > leave some specific ergonomic feedback from the perspective of a
 > testr/setuptools user:
 > 
 > * Running a subset of the tests using `tox -epy27 <regex>` worked
 > the same
 > * Re-running failing tests using `tox -epy27 -- --failing` worked
 > the same
 > * I wish I had known about the --no-discover option years ago.
 > Honestly this is what I want instead of a regex 100% of the time.
 > Discovery is slooooow.

To be fair this isn't something that was in testr at all. I hacked it into
ostestr by just subprocessing out to subunit.run instead of testr. When
I started stestr I made sure to include it there.

 > * It reports failure data (stack trace, logs) as soon as a test
 > fails so I can get to work debugging immediately instead of like 6
 > minutes later. This is a huge improvement over ostestr.
 > * The 6500 lines of scrollback (the reason I previously reverted
 > os-testr from Heat) is still infuriating and makes me want to throw
 > my computer out of a window.

From my POV this one of those classic religious divides over personal preference.
Frankly speaking the minority of people fall into the camp where they want the silent
output except on failures while most people like seeing the real time output of
tests as they run. This is why most projects ended up using ostestr or cargo
culting a pretty_tox.sh script from somewhere. This why in stestr (and pretty much
every test runner I've used, except testr) defaults this way and gives users options
to change the output to their preference.

That being said you have to remember that tox is used for CI too, and in a CI environment
having progress displayed is important.  If you check the console output from a job and it
doesn't print anything for 30min while the tests are running you have no idea of what's
going on.

 > * The --quiet option does nothing AFAICT.

Yeah, this was a bug which should be fixed on the current master. (although IIRC it
redirects stdout to /dev/null which may be too quiet :) )

 > * Adding the --no-subunit-trace option *after* the 'run' subcommand
 > gets rid of the excess output. I submitted a patch to do that in
 > Heat (I9fe8cc6a540c48d7fc04cef5e65e87dc3cce52fe), and I'd suggest
 > including it in the recommendation here.

I don't think we want that in the tox.ini at all, it's a user preference thing.
The point of this review is to start standardizing on uniform behavior and
definition for how running tests works.

There is an open ask from mordred (I'm still waiting for him or someone else to
file an issue with the details) to enable a local config to set defaults for CLI
options. So you can have a global config file that says default to
--no-subunit-trace on your system. I'm totally in favor of adding that to stestr
if it makes it more use able for people.

 > * It's confusing that unknown options are silently ignored
 > (https://github.com/mtreinish/stestr/issues/99), especially when
 > some options have to go before and some after the subcommand.

This also should be fixed on master. (the subcommand ordering thing drives me
crazy too)"}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2018-01-16 20:34:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Yes please.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2018-01-17 19:59:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> To be fair this isn't something that was in testr at all. I hacked it into
> ostestr by just subprocessing out to subunit.run instead of testr. When
> I started stestr I made sure to include it there.

Thank you for this!!! It's a shame we can't easily make this the default.

> From my POV this one of those classic religious divides over personal preference. 

Heh, perhaps :)

Objectively speaking, though, the tests are >10% slower with the subunit-trace output enabled.  I'm sure for some people the entertainment value of 6000+ lines of debug going by is more than enough to warrant the extra 45s wait, but personally I'm only interested in getting back to work asap. (Insert your own joke about some religious group here.)

> That being said you have to remember that tox is used for CI too, and in a CI environment having progress displayed is important.

Totally agree here. It would be great if there were some easy way to always force it on in the tox gate jobs. From my perspective the ideal would be:

* Off by default
* Jobs where it always make sense (low to moderate # of slow tests) can enable it via the CLI in tox.ini
* Projects that really like it can enable it in .stestr.conf
* The gate can enable it with an environment variable

Mainly because it would be a little weird for an environment variable to override a config file or the CLI. In a pinch we could have something like STESTR_FORCE_SUBUNIT_TRACE_ON=True though.

> There is an open ask from mordred (I'm still waiting for him or someone else to file an issue with the details) to enable a local config to set defaults for CLI options. So you can have a global config file that says default to --no-subunit-trace on your system. I'm totally in favor of adding that to stestr if it makes it more use able for people.

That'd definitely be better than nothing. (It would solve the problem for me, but probably still result in a lot of other people suffering needlessly.)"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2018-01-19 14:13:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

...or we could switch to verbose mode dynamically if someone actually is connecting to the log firehose to watch lines pass by. That way tests would *really* go slower if you watch them :)'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2018-01-19 14:49:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2018-01-22 06:33:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Rollcall-Vote+1 Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:26:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Majority reached, to be approved on Friday if no new objection is posted.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2018-01-26 15:28:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow+1'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-14 20:43:19.000000000', 'message': 'Update Python PTI for tests to be specific and explicit

This commit updates the language in the Python PTI to be much more
specific about how projects should be running tests. This is done so we
can have a consistent experience between projects when running tests.
The current state of affairs is far from ideal in that there are about
7 different ways projects run python unit tests. (some don't even comply
with the looser previous PTI) For example::

 * PBR's testr entrpoint "python setup.py test"
   https://github.com/openstack-dev/pbr/blob/master/pbr/testr_command.py
 * testr's setup tools entrypoint "python setup.py testr"
   https://github.com/openstack-dev/pbr/blob/master/pbr/testr_command.py
 * pretty_tox.sh wrapper scripts and variants
   (this was cargo culted from tempest and diverged significantly
    between each projects' forks)
 * ostestr (which is part of the os-testr package, but it's not the
   only thing there)
 * nostests (the horizon case for django testing will likely be a
   continued exception)
 * proboscis

(which are just the examples I know of off the top of my head) For
anyone trying to work in multiple projects navigating this can be
quite tricky, especially when trying to debug a failure. To clean this
up, this patch defines one way to run python tests.

Besides making the wording more explicit and providing specific this
commit also tries to provide some additional background information on
why we use stestr. It's not always obvious the advantages it provides
us, so this attempts to document it at a high level for the ages.

Change-Id: I2637dd714cbb6d38ef8b8dc1083e359207118284

commit_message:
Update Python PTI for tests to be specific and explicit

This commit updates the language in the Python PTI to be much more
specific about how projects should be running tests. This is done so we
can have a consistent experience between projects when running tests.
The current state of affairs is far from ideal in that there are about
7 different ways projects run python unit tests. (some don't even comply
with the looser previous PTI) For example::

 * PBR's testr entrpoint "python setup.py test"
   https://github.com/openstack-dev/pbr/blob/master/pbr/testr_command.py
 * testr's setup tools entrypoint "python setup.py testr"
   https://github.com/testing-cabal/testrepository/blob/master/testrepository/setuptools_command.py
 * pretty_tox.sh wrapper scripts and variants
   (this was cargo culted from tempest and diverged significantly
    between each projects' forks)
 * ostestr (which is part of the os-testr package, but it's not the
   only thing there)
 * nosetests (the horizon case for django testing will likely be a
   continued exception)
 * proboscis

(which are just the examples I know of off the top of my head) For
anyone trying to work in multiple projects navigating this can be
quite tricky, especially when trying to debug a failure. To clean this
up, this patch defines one way to run python tests.

Besides making the wording more explicit and providing specifics this
commit also tries to provide some additional background information on
why we use stestr. It's not always obvious the advantages it provides
us, so this attempts to document it at a high level for the ages.

Change-Id: I2637dd714cbb6d38ef8b8dc1083e359207118284

commit_message:
Allow public polling to choose release names

Release naming polls originally were conducted as public polls
in Launchpad (requiring only a Launchpad account). Then we moved
to CIVS-driven Condorcet polls, with personal voting links to
all Foundation members (requiring a Foundation membership to vote).

Due to limitations in the CIVS service, it's currently not practical
to send Condorcet voting links to every Foundation member. Instead
we'll use the public voting feature of CIVS, and allow anyone with
the link to cast their vote.

That opens the vote to ballot stuffing, but the choice is not that
critical, the proposed names all follow strict criteria, and there
are many safeguards in place to exclude bad names (from a legal or
marketing standpoint). So it feels safe enough to use public voting,
originally disseminating the voting URL through the openstack
mailing-lists.

Change-Id: I2f4b7fb24ccfb54403d0dedc0a757af3c6769d61

commit_message:
Remove leftovers from mongodb

MongoDB is not longer the default or recommended backend for
OpenStack services and services are using other data stores.

This patch removes mongodb puppet module installation from p-o-i
and hiera config file.

Change-Id: I3d437ea6f5cfe6a887903ffb4da009439cf144e9

commit_message:
Start moving users of parted to privsep.

This isn't all calls, but a step along the way. Note that I moved
a xenapi unit test to being the first unit test for privsep directly.
I'm not sure if I love this way of testing (having the "meat" of
the method undecorated and having a wrapper), but I've been unable
to come up with a way to mock away the entrypoint wrapper.

Change-Id: I35d4e7c6c43cbcbc1549aa28796ff97f447a4b03
blueprint: hurrah-for-privsep

commit_message:
Fix update_cell to ignore existing identical cells

The recent cell duplication filter makes it impossible to do update_cell
on an existing cell with identical details. If we're updating a cell by
uuid and specify the exact same parameters, we shouldn't signal failure.

Change-Id: I2faaec94444bc7d29fda1facd22e0da3bc6f01f9
Closes-Bug: #1744780

commit_message:
Remove use of unsupported TEMPEST_SERVICES variable

TEMPEST_SERVICES global variable is not supported
by devstack since long back.
- I380dd20e5ed716a0bdf92aa02c3730359b8136e4
- I9c24705e494689f09a885eb0a640efd50db33fcf

Service availability of tempest known services will be
set by devstack with local check.
- I02be777bf93143d946ccbb8e9eff637bfd1928d4

searchlight does not have tempest plugin so it does
not need to have service register in tempest.

This commit removes the TEMPEST_SERVICES setting.

Change-Id: I0467b38dbb0abe99d26c948dccd57bfe67acbcad
Related-Bug: #1743688

subject: Add CentOS 7 deployment support
messages:
[{'account_id': 27317, 'date': '2017-11-21 09:52:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2017-11-21 09:53:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2017-11-21 09:58:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Thanks for putting this together! Can you also please add the config to zuul.d/project.yaml so that the centos build is actually executed.

It'll need to be the same as https://github.com/openstack/openstack-ansible-os_glance/blob/45d84bf792bbabd43fc100e37f8ea29504544b1c/zuul.d/project.yaml#L21 and be present in both the check and gate queues."}, {'account_id': 27317, 'date': '2017-11-21 10:13:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2017-11-21 11:08:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Great - it looks like it's working!

The lint failure will be resolved by https://review.openstack.org/521812 - once that merges this patch can be rechecked by commenting: recheck"}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2017-11-21 11:09:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
First release of neutron-vpnaas-dashboard as neutron team

This is the first release of neutron-vpnaas-dashboard
after neutron-vpnaas is back to the neutron stadium.
The latest release of neutron-vpnaas-dashboard is 1.1.0,
so the new version will be 1.2.0.

Change-Id: Ib4c8790a9c0af9754a6d249ee2925fcc289d8f91

commit_message:
Remove log translations

Log messages are no longer being translated. This removes all use of the
_LE, _LI, and _LW translation markers to simplify logging and to avoid
confusion with new contributions.

See:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-i18n/2016-November/002574.html
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-March/113365.html

Change-Id: Ic22cf715a70e9e1ff734944015d2f8a1ab2dbef8

[{'account_id': 21479, 'date': '2018-01-22 09:19:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 23498, 'date': '2018-01-22 11:06:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Testing completed on the zVM Driver CI system check-nova pipeline and failed.  To recheck only the zVM driver plugins, submit a comment with only  zvm: recheck in the comment.. Contact information: zvmosci@us.ibm.com. For information see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ZVMDriver.

- check-nova-master http://extbasicopstackcilog01.podc.sl.edst.ibm.com/test_logs/jenkins-check-nova-master-12764 : FAILURE in 1h 43m 46s'}, {'account_id': 21479, 'date': '2018-01-22 11:29:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-01-22 15:05:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

I think this is insufficient in that it's missing a lot of other instance properties that change before we cast to conductor and fail to schedule, plus it's potentially nulling out the image_ref for a failed evacuate during scheduling.

It's probably easiest to just give up and put the instance into ERROR state if there is a failure during scheduling for rebuild and then it's upon the user to rebuild with a valid image to fix things, but let's not try rolling back in conductor what the API screwed up."}, {'account_id': 21813, 'date': '2018-01-22 15:19:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Thanks.

Agree that merely putting an instance in ERROR state without touching metadata would be the easiest solving of the issue.
An ideal way IMO is to make all instance changes in a transactional manner while rebuilding but with cast call it is not the case.

I don't see the reason why we do the workaround for particular exceptions
only. Explain, please, if I am wrong."}, {'account_id': 26515, 'date': '2018-01-22 16:07:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Build succeeded.

- nova-dsvm-full-tempest http://cloudbase-ci.com/nova/536268/2/ : SUCCESS in 3h 09m 21s'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2018-01-22 16:15:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So, I was thinking the ERROR indication would be sufficient as well. However, users can get themselves out of ERROR jail with a stop/start cycle, which means post-rebuild-failure I could get my instance back to active with the wrong image details set. A reboot cycle would be the first thing I'd try if I wasn't sure what happened, and thus I'm not sure that solution is all that much different than what we have today which is buggy. A transient indication that must be acted on in a very specific way in order to restore consistency is not that great..."}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2018-01-22 17:25:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I find it pretty poor form that we're setting a bunch of instance attributes in the API layer and then casting to the conductor for an operation that could fail. Could we move all of that changing of instance attributes to the conductor so that it can clean up after itself properly if the rebuild doesn't go through? I guess I'm basically on board with Andrey's idea of "make all instance changes in a transactional manner."'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-01-22 18:35:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Agreed with the points called out here. Setting the image attributes in compute/api is a holdover from back when rebuild couldn't fail from scheduling (scheduler used to be bypassed). So maybe it would be best if we changed that to delay setting them until we know whether scheduling picked a host.

The question is, even if we do that, how do we tell the end user that rebuild failed? We could put the instance in ERROR state (but with the correct original imageref etc) but then we again have the problem of, "how will the end user know what to do about the ERROR state?" The instance is still fine and working, but their rebuild failed.'}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2018-01-22 18:46:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Long term we might need a better way to handle async operations that return 202 accepted but can then fail.

In the meantime, I don't think we have anything better than setting the instance to ERROR, with an appropriate error message in the 'fault' attribute."}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-01-22 18:56:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yep, I know. Again the "Tasks API" comes to mind.

I was thinking about the fault message too. AFAIK, that field defaults to admin-only so I wasn't thinking it's super helpful to an end user. At my last company, we enabled the field via policy so end users could see it. Maybe that's a different default these days.'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-01-23 01:30:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> I was thinking about the fault message too. AFAIK, that field
 > defaults to admin-only so I wasn't thinking it's super helpful to
 > an end user. At my last company, we enabled the field via policy so
 > end users could see it. Maybe that's a different default these
 > days.

I just tried a test in devstack and it's only the fault "details" that are admin-only, like the original traceback.

So we should be good to go with setting a meaningful fault message that's visible to a normal user about the fact that the rebuild failed.

The only potential issue I could imagine there is if the user prefers to keep their instance as-is and keep working with it, it will remain in ERROR state. They could get blocked if the instance being in ERROR state prevents them from taking various new action on the instance (if ERROR is an invalid state in a check_instance_state decorated method). I think a normal user could get out of that kind of ERROR state jail by rebooting though, so maybe that's not that bad.'}, {'account_id': 21479, 'date': '2018-01-23 01:47:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks all, until now there are follow some ways to resolve this issue:

1. Do nothing except setting server status to ERROR, easiest.
2. Move instance change codes from API to Conductor.
3. Save all original system metadata with a prefix like "original_xxx", we can easily restore those data if fail to schedule later.

I prefer No.2.'}, {'account_id': 21479, 'date': '2018-01-23 12:39:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2018-01-23 15:00:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 26515, 'date': '2018-01-23 15:07:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Build succeeded.

- nova-dsvm-full-tempest http://cloudbase-ci.com/nova/536268/3/ : SUCCESS in 2h 28m 10s'}, {'account_id': 21479, 'date': '2018-01-23 15:16:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:02:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:11:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> 1. Do nothing except setting server status to ERROR, easiest. 2. Move instance change codes from API to Conductor. 3. Save all original system metadata with a prefix like "original_xxx", we can easily restore those data if fail to schedule later.

#1 with a fault on the instance is easiest and backportable.

#2 is best long-term but not backportable. I think what we'd want to do is like cold migrate, the API does an RPC call to conductor, and conductor does an RPC cast to compute. Then if scheduling fails in conductor, we can rollback (or just not commit the changes) before returning the failure to the user.

3. I don't like this option at all since it's still just specific to one thing that is being changed, but the rebuild API can change several fields on the instance, not just metadata.'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:16:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:16:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:19:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

LGTM as a short-term solution and with the fault message breadcrumb and ERROR status to the user that something failed during scheduling.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:21:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:40:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:41:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Set server status to ERROR if rebuild failed

Currently there is no indication that the rebuild was refused,
and worse, we may have a wrong imageref for the instance.

This patch set the instance to ERROR status if rebuild failed in the
scheduling stage. The user can rebuild the instance with valid image
to get it out of ERROR state and reset with right instance metadata and
properties.

Closes-Bug: 1744325

Change-Id: Ibb7bee15a3d4ee6f0ef53ba12e8b41f65a1fe999

commit_message:
Workaround eventlet bug with recent py 2.7.12

Increasing ES RAM to 64m as well since it's failing to
start (suspected OOM)

Closes-Bug: #1745194
Change-Id: I0f0ea5398e21c4f8aa506ee523dd33d436abc7d1

Since it's possible to have a role assignment on the system now, we

bp system-scope

commit_message:
Relay system information in RoleAssignmentNotFound

Since it's possible to have a role assignment on the system now, we
should make sure we handle that case in the RoleAssignmentNotFound
exception

bp system-scope

Change-Id: I2388d65ffa5b68690d9c4f0dd16f16e158f5a091

'}, {'created': '2014-12-15 13:16:48.000000000', 'message': 'Add the Nova libvirt StorPool attachment driver.

StorPool is distributed data storage software running on standard x86
servers.  StorPool aggregates the performance and capacity of all drives
into a shared pool of storage distributed among the servers.  Within
this storage pool the user creates thin-provisioned volumes that are
exposed to the clients as block devices.  StorPool consists of two parts
wrapped in one package - a server and a client.  The StorPool server
allows a hypervisor to act as a storage node, while the StorPool client
allows a hypervisor node to access the storage pool and act as a compute
node.  In OpenStack terms the StorPool solution allows each hypervisor
node to be both a storage and a compute node simultaneously.

This driver allows StorPool volumes defined in Cinder to be attached as
additional disks to a virtual machine.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3d40009eb17d054f33b3ed641643e285ba094ec2
Implements: blueprint libvirt-storpool-volume-attach
