commit_message:
Add the Nova libvirt StorPool attachment driver.

StorPool is distributed data storage software running on standard x86
servers.  StorPool aggregates the performance and capacity of all drives
into a shared pool of storage distributed among the servers.  Within
this storage pool the user creates thin-provisioned volumes that are
exposed to the clients as block devices.  StorPool consists of two parts
wrapped in one package - a server and a client.  The StorPool server
allows a hypervisor to act as a storage node, while the StorPool client
allows a hypervisor node to access the storage pool and act as a compute
node.  In OpenStack terms the StorPool solution allows each hypervisor
node to be both a storage and a compute node simultaneously.

This driver allows StorPool volumes defined in Cinder to be attached as
additional disks to a virtual machine.

Change-Id: I3d40009eb17d054f33b3ed641643e285ba094ec2
Implements: blueprint libvirt-storpool-volume-attach

commit_message:
Add scope_types to implied role policies

Today, keystone doesn't support the ability to create roles and
immediately start using them without modifying policy files
across multiple services. Since role management is technically
considered a system-level resource because of this reason, it makes
sense to have implied role policies system-level as well.

From now on, a warning will be logged when a project-scoped token is
used to imply roles. Operators will be able to opt into requiring
system-scoped tokens for these policies by enabling oslo.policy's
`enforce_scope` configuration option, which will result in an
HTTP Forbidden exception when mismatching scope is used.

Change-Id: I9ec3bf02904dfe3773164e410db822a81ff213e2

[{'created': '2017-12-13 11:22:16.000000000', 'message': 'Sync cinder policy

Based on cinder commit 55b2f349514fce1ffde5fd2244cfc26d7daad6a6

The new file was generated by oslopolicy-sample-generator.
nova uses policy-in-code now, so there is a lot of differences.
Sorted version diff is http://paste.openstack.org/show/628744/

Removed policies are:

backup:backup-export
consistencygroup:create
consistencygroup:create_cgsnapshot
consistencygroup:delete
consistencygroup:delete_cgsnapshot
consistencygroup:get
consistencygroup:get_all
consistencygroup:get_all_cgsnapshots
consistencygroup:get_cgsnapshot
consistencygroup:update
default
volume:get_volume_admin_metadata
volume_extension:replication:promote
volume_extension:replication:reenable
volume_extension:types_extra_specs

Horizon still uses consistency group panel, so the removed policies
related to consistency group are still required.
They are added as cinder_policy.d/consistencygroup.json.

Change-Id: I3292fae2b9d2b368954bfbaa19df391d3860bdfe

commit_message:
Sync cinder policy

Based on cinder commit 55b2f349514fce1ffde5fd2244cfc26d7daad6a6

The new file was generated by oslopolicy-sample-generator.
nova uses policy-in-code now, so there is a lot of differences.
Sorted version diff is http://paste.openstack.org/show/628744/

Removed policies are:

backup:backup-export
consistencygroup:create
consistencygroup:create_cgsnapshot
consistencygroup:delete
consistencygroup:delete_cgsnapshot
consistencygroup:get
consistencygroup:get_all
consistencygroup:get_all_cgsnapshots
consistencygroup:get_cgsnapshot
consistencygroup:update
default
volume:get_volume_admin_metadata
volume_extension:replication:promote
volume_extension:replication:reenable
volume_extension:types_extra_specs

Horizon still uses consistency group panel, so the removed policies
related to consistency group are still required.
They are added as cinder_policy.d/consistencygroup.json.

Change-Id: I3292fae2b9d2b368954bfbaa19df391d3860bdfe

commit_message:
Improve limit sql backend

This patch does:
1. Improve the error message as Morgan suggested before.
2. Add a new error type: RegisteredLimitError.
3. Catch the DBReferenceError in update/delete resigtered limit
functions.
4. Handle the case that region_id=None for update/delete
registered limits.
5. Fix a code error in create_limits function.

Change-Id: Id572348ca7867d7ce6f258cb3132b05a313624bd
bp: unified-limits

repos/OpenStack/glance/.tox/py35/lib/python3.5/site-packages/oslo_db/sqlalchemy/test_base.py:175: DeprecationWarning

commit_message:
Execute py35 functional tests under py35 environment

Recently merged patch [1] causes py35 functional tests under py27
environment. As a result py35 functional tests also hangs (refer
bug [2]). The reason for this is in patch [1] intended to use already
created environment using 'envdir' variable but somehow it uses py27
environment instead of py35 environment.

Removed 'envdir' from functional and functional-py35 section so that
it can creates its own environment for execution.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/474816/
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1744824

Change-Id: I405b3718358b9977384696c8f004ffb2cf922ef5

commit_message:
Correct plugin test location reporting

Commit 6f67e3787338407e637d80a6fad0edb5f9a08b24 changed the
directory structure for the plugin, but the code that reports
where the tests can be found was not fully updated.

This updates the plugin reporting to get the correct directory
for tempest to look in and cleans up a few nits with the file.

Change-Id: Ib89f7a9493e3d83382d8dd1f07a3e9e4bb4fcd80
Closes-bug: #1745175

commit_message:
Added the ability to specify checksum for etcd

It is possibe for the user to override te etcd version, thus download a
different etcd file, but the checksum is constant, so the checksum
verification will fail in that case.
Added the ability to specify a different checksum, so the user would be
able to specify the new version checksum

Change-Id: I85af3af841ae957964f18d4e37a86ab0703882bc
Closes-Bug: #1736718

commit_message:
usage: split out the limit related logic into ProjectUsageView

Previously limit information was always retrieved but it is not
used in the admin overview. This commit moves the limit related logic
into a separate class ProjectUsageView.

testing of usage.views is covered by individual panel tests,
so UTs for panels which uses UsageView rather than the new
ProjectUsageView need to be updated in this commit.

blueprint make-quotas-great-again
Change-Id: Id93b66d11e3b0c98d1fbb0454bb43984c2999d92

If the resource provider exists but its child resource providers are not
present in the local cache, this method will not retrieve them from

'}]
commit_message:
fix _ensure_resource_provider()

If the resource provider exists but its child resource providers are not
present in the local cache, this method will not retrieve them from
placement and callers will not have an up-to-date tree upon successful
return.

This patch fixes this by always retrieving providers that needs to be
refreshed from placement.

Change-Id: Ib113ca99207842d9dab56773a1a4f38fb79e7b88

We were looking for the existence of the 'external_ids' command
in all tables. However, as floating ips and subnets are fetched
prior this check, it still fails if the OVSDB schema doesn't
include the column in any of the tables.

This patch is moving the check upwards to avoid the failure.

Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez <dalvarez@redhat.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Fix RDO OVN scenario job by checking DB schema (iii)

We were looking for the existence of the 'external_ids' command
in all tables. However, as floating ips and subnets are fetched
prior this check, it still fails if the OVSDB schema doesn't
include the column in any of the tables.

This patch is moving the check upwards to avoid the failure.

Closes-Bug: #1740698
Change-Id: If4c64c428d3c474f08cb0441a2c1653fb0095d37
Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez <dalvarez@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Change django.utils.log.NullHandler to logging.NullHandler

django.utils.log.NullHandler was removed in Django 1.9. logging.NullHandler
wad added to Python standard library since 2.7 so we should use it now.

Change-Id: I38f3f1d592f5456efc7dc94c0677a0a594722fbd

commit_message:
DNM: DEBUG Update quickstart extras with undercloud install for containers

Add WIP patches I20a73f1ca761873b6897f32c07eec377d3769a79 and
I29f55d0717d0980d18cb7e6ee2941b376a97fac4 for undercloud containers
CI WIP I7d056b208d5ac0639e3277f3f4ae453a9ee639e8, to debug
why rabbit fails to start in a container:

Collect most of var/lib/heat-config directory.

This add the heat agent notifications, and ensure we dont miss any
new agent (heat-config-docker-cmd).

It include the deployed/<hash>.json as it contains information about
the resource that triggered the script.

Add more directories to collect

This patch adds /var/lib/config-data and /var/lib/kolla/config_files to
collected logs to help developers to debug Pike and newer versions of TripleO.
/var/lib was sorted alphanumerically for readability reasons.

Change-Id: Ia51c18d3bcf2c9350dfd82f41e40c5facee54b8d

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-25 23:26:18.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid simultaneous restarts

It is possible for two or more percona-cluster units to simultaneously
attempt to restart and join the cluster. When this race condition
occurs one unit may error with:
"Failed to start mysql (max retries reached)"

We already have the control mechanism distributed_wait used in other
charms. This change implements this mechanism for percona-cluster.

Configuration options allow for fine tuning. The balance is time vs
tolerance for collision errors. CI systems may tolerate the occasion
false positive for time saved. Where production deployments can
sacrifice a bit of time for a guaranteed deploy.

Change-Id: I52e7f8e410ecd77a7a142d44b43414e33eff3a6e
Closes-Bug: #1745432
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid simultaneous restarts

It is possible for two or more percona-cluster units to simultaneously
attempt to restart and join the cluster. When this race condition
occurs one unit may error with:
"Failed to start mysql (max retries reached)"

We already have the control mechanism distributed_wait used in other
charms. This change implements this mechanism for percona-cluster.

Configuration options allow for fine tuning. The balance is time vs
tolerance for collision errors. CI systems may tolerate the occasion
false positive for time saved. Where production deployments can
sacrifice a bit of time for a guaranteed deploy.

Change-Id: I52e7f8e410ecd77a7a142d44b43414e33eff3a6e
Closes-Bug: #1745432

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-29 15:17:19.000000000', 'message': "Add L7 routing support for openshift context.

An OpenShift route is a way to expose a service by giving it an externally-reachable hostname like www.example.com.

The L7 routing functionality is composed of :
1. L7 Route
2. L7 Router

L7 Route - define a L7 route entry, which actually mapped an hostname for a service.
A L7 route is eqvivalnt to IP route entry in L3 Routing terms.

L7 Router - The L7 router is responsible for performing  the L7 routing (based on rules defined by L7 routes).
The router uses the service selector to find the service and the endpoints backing the service.

This commit implements L7 Router capability based on Neutron L7 Policy/Rule capability, and add support
for OCP 'Route' objects (for defining L7 Route rule/entry).

The general idea for future support of k8s ingress controller, is to re-use L7 Router, and
develop ingress controller handler that will generate the L7 Routes.

Change-Id: Iee1384cfc41e76f9ebbdf865923ab1273dd40883
Implements: blueprint 	openshift-router-support

commit_message:
[WIP] Add Support for L7 routing.

This PR should handle the common part of L7 Routing,
It's includes :
Enable L7 Router engine including L7 router driver

Current code  includes :
Common part + OCP Route part

Action items :
Eliminate the 'non common' code
On which SW context the L7 Router engione should run ?

Change-Id: Iee1384cfc41e76f9ebbdf865923ab1273dd40883
Implements: blueprint 	openshift-router-support

commit_message:
Correct location of venv build logs

In [1] the intent was to have each venv build log
to its own log file. This makes troubleshooting a
lot easier due to the verbosity of the output in
the log - this at least separates each venv's
output. Unfortunately this extra CLI option was
supposed to be removed. This patch completes the
original intent.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/470757

Change-Id: I714d160a39beb870ba66db11a60cf0241ca770f3
(cherry picked from commit 12611a94408421daecdb7daad18ba857cbaba794)

commit_message:
Modify the test case of get_disk_mapping_rescue_with_config

Now running the test on AArch64 will get mismatch error, since
the default cdrom type on AArch64 is scsi, while the default cdrom
on X86 is ide, so I tweak the test and add AArch64 support.

Closes-bug: #1711093

Change-Id: I552f164107824fa28bfb47974c737da7d0f47e15
Signed-off-by: Kevin Zhao <kevin.zhao@arm.com>

commit_message:
Minor fix to remove legacy OVSDB IDL connection

Upon failure to create an OVSDB connection using IDL with the ovsdbapp
lib, a second attempt will be executed using legacy ovsdapp connection
api.  This patch removes the legacy connection attempt.

Change-Id: I07477ec92ba5e95794f91bf67cab97e9dca89dde
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Remove foreign key for registered limit

Now registered limit table has two foreign keys, one for service
id, another for region id. But catalog and limit may use different
backend, in that case, the fks will lead error. Such as, if catalog
use file based backend, registered limit will can never be created.

So we should drop the fks in the table and add the resouce existence
check logic in code.

Change-Id: Ic98e069a03931bb3eaaad63cd2db7e6a822a3546
bp: unified-limits

This commit contains two fixes:
1. ``of_listen_address``: We use the xenapi's facts directly, so
that we can avoid depending on facts gathered by setup for hosts;
This is useful when deploy on the role of neutron only (--tag neutron);
2. ``local_ip``: Get the proper IP for tunnel. It should be chosen

commit_message:
XenAPI: fix two neutron configures

This commit contains two fixes:
1. ``of_listen_address``: We use the xenapi's facts directly, so
that we can avoid depending on facts gathered by setup for hosts;
This is useful when deploy on the role of neutron only (--tag neutron);
2. ``local_ip``: Get the proper IP for tunnel. It should be chosen
from dom0's IP which is in the same network where tunnel interface
is connected.

blueprint: xenserver-support

Change-Id: I61bbd6499323e3fddd6293a0df6baec34dbddf23

commit_message:
XenAPI: support provider networks

When enabled provider networks; the neutron-openvswith-agent-xenapi
should use proper bridge_mappings which should have dom0's bridges
where the VMs' vifs actually connected to for the interfaces defined
in the configure option of *neutron_external_interface*.

Depends-On: I9a6bebe19ed488bb2173d5dc2daa14e236411243
Change-Id: I44f59c69d25b8400e1b936fcdf8f21b5c4168f1f

[{'created': '2018-01-25 09:45:45.000000000', 'message': 'bgpvpn: agent extension, do not skip processing when RT are empty

Skipping processing for a BGPVPN when RTs are empty
results, with the current code, in failing to update
the RTs to empty RTs (bug 1732070).

This change removes this very marginal optimization.

Change-Id: I615acd193a90eeea2ab3dd9bd3b41912a6304193
Closes-Bug: 1732070
'}, {'created': '2018-01-25 09:47:15.000000000', 'message': 'bgpvpn: agent extension, do not skip processing when RTs are empty

Skipping processing for a BGPVPN when RTs are empty
results, with the current code, in also failing to
update the RTs to empty RTs (bug 1732070).

This change removes this very marginal optimization.

commit_message:
bgpvpn: agent extension, do not skip processing when RTs are empty

Skipping processing for a BGPVPN when RTs are empty
results, with the current code, in also failing to
update the RTs to empty RTs (bug 1732070).

This change removes this very marginal optimization.

Change-Id: I615acd193a90eeea2ab3dd9bd3b41912a6304193
Closes-Bug: 1732070

commit_message:
Pass OSC interface through to barbican plugin

python-openstackclient uses OS_INTERFACE or --os-interface to select a
catalog endpoint to work with. The barbican CLI uses BARBICAN_INTERFACE
or --interface, which OSC won't pass through. This is a problem because
the it prevents the user from selecting a non-public endpoint when using
barbican via openstackclient rather than as a standalone CLI. This patch
updates the osc plugin to pass through the interface set by OSC to the
barbican client class.

Change-Id: I1e9890c9e87fb77b272f939bf33914df739aa5be

commit_message:
Sync keystone policy

Based on keystone commit cfbc2aa30b7406b4bc77e40a55561d1f46174b5c

keystone uses policy-in-code now, so there is a lot of differences.
The new file was generated by oslopolicy-sample-generator.

Sorted version diff is http://paste.openstack.org/show/628745/.

Removed policies are:
  default
  identity:change_password
  identity:get_identity_providers

'identity:change_password' is used in horizon.
There seems no corresponding new policy, so the corresponding horizon
rules are dropped in this commit.

Our UT depends on the identity policy file.
This commit updates the UTs in a more robust way.

Change-Id: I76eb9f95c7112bcbad75ee151f363f892298d081

commit_message:
Add trigger verification in API

Currently, we use 'cast' instead of 'call' to send request
from api to operationengine when creating a new trigger.
With 'cast', it will not give a return value to api even the
trigger is invalid, so users can create triggers successfully
with using invalid triggers.

This patch add trigger verification in API side. Before send
create request to operationengine, API send a verify request
to operationengine first, which type is 'call', to make sure
the trigger will be created is valid.

Change-Id: Iea734e1b4a63f6e35afe32cbbb2b60f79d6db085
Closes-Bug: #1736657

commit_message:
Add a parameter to be able to override clients_keystone/auth_uri.

It is usually the same as auth_url which is defined there
$::heat::keystone::authtoken::auth_url.  We can now point this to
another part of the catalog (ie, public vs internal for instance).

Co-Authored-By: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovat@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I4429d86d831f49f1bc0fef04379a81ada20b6ab6

commit_message:
[WIP]Add Cyborg SPDK Driver

SPDKDRIVER is a virtual interface which provides common methods
for specific drivers (such as: VHOSTDRIVER, NVMFDRIVER, etc.).
For this reason, the Cyborg agent should invoke these drivers
via py-spdk to communicate with the backend SPDK-base app server.
The py-spdk is management lib for SPDK applications which need to
be imported into the cyborg, the import.yml add the operation.

For example:
When the Cyborg agent call the NVMFDRIVER.discover_accelerator(),
the return value we get is:
{
    'server': 'vhost',
    'bdevs': [{
       "num_blocks": 131072,
       "name": "nvme1",
       "block_size": 512,
       ......
     }]
    'subsystems': [{
       "core": 0,
       "nqn": "nqn.2018-01.org.nvmexpress.discovery",
       "hosts": [],
       ......
     }]
}

Change-Id: Ieee6a8be3c112c4af58fee174c65e2985e4bd725

commit_message:
Implement GET /v3/auth/system

Keystone has APIs for retrieving projects and domains based on the
role assignments a user has on projects and domains. We should
introduce similar functionality for system assignments. This will
make discovering system access for users and client easier.

bp system-scope

Change-Id: Iab577fcd1b57b8b5593c3f9d50a772466383a999

commit_message:
Deprecate the ceilometer collector

The Ceilometer API has been deprecated for a while now. Some of the meter
types queried by the collector (instance, image) have been removed from the
Telemetry project in the Ocata release.

In order to make sure that the warning will be seen, it has been put in the
constructor of the Worker class.

We should completely remove the collector during the next release cycle.

Change-Id: Ieaa2bc585d0cbcf7b035da627e189c920c9a8e08

For the remaining points, I'm still working (and testing) as the 'WIP' says, but reviews are welcome!"}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2017-12-20 10:37:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2017-12-21 09:01:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2017-12-21 09:06:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-09 16:27:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-16 10:10:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-17 08:56:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-17 10:17:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-17 10:40:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Hi Luka! Nice review! Thanks to you I could fix some list() functions that I forgot. Thanks!
About the radosgw.objects.size, I think it was wrong from the begining, as we can't valorize a value in GB if we divide it by GB. I changed both factor and unit: we now are dividing by GB and so using B unit for the final value.

Correct me if I'm wrong but, about the qty field, if you look at the source code more closely, you will see that I retrieve it between lines 271 and 277. But for those with qty at 1, we don't enter in any if/elif statement case. And so, the int case is treated at line 330.

About the units, I changed the one in Gnocchi collector from MB to MiB for the image metrics, because we were already using MiB for conversion, but wrongly using MB as the final unit. That was a mix between decimal and binary units. I don't think that the same mistake was done anywhere else."}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-17 11:23:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

Hi Martin!

- Concerning RadosGW: If we divide B by 1024^3, we obtain GiB. So the right config would either be unit=GiB and factor=1/1073741824 OR unit=B and factor=1

- About the qty field: When metrics.yml is provided, qty is retrieved at line 266. So for network.floating, instance and default_unit, a KeyError is raised at line 299. Maybe you could wrap it in an if statement "if not isinstance(qty, int): convert_unit()". Also, check that qty is either a string or an int. If qty is of any other numeric type (float...), an exception will be raised at l. 325.

- About the units: Units are always binary, excepted for network metrics (these have decimal units by convention). Most of the time, *B units are actually *iB (we also say mega when we should say mebi). But if we specify one unit as *iB, we should make clear which units are binary and which are decimal to avoid confusions.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-17 14:20:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-17 14:29:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10: Patch Set 9 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-17 14:42:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hi Luka. Thanks for you feedbacks!
I finally realized what I didn't understood the first time about the radosgw, thanks for your explanations!

About the units, as you said me that Cloudkitty was using the wrong "unit family" from the beginning, I changed everything. Now, decimal units are used only for network metrics, and binary units are used everywhere else.

About the unit conversion, I added a if statement to check if the value is string type or not, as you suggested and as I did in my other PoC. The only thing that changes is that thedeprecated message will not be logged anymore if the if statement is not satisfied (but this log was an error in that case, thanks you again).

But I don't agree with the fact that we should test other types here (e.g.: float type). That means that we should do the test in other collectors too (monasca.py l. 352). We should make instead a configuration validator for this kind of tasks. This check should be done at Cloudkitty startup and before entering in collector code. We use the '1' value here as an hack, but not other numerical value is expected here.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-17 15:32:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-23 13:14:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2

LGTM! Thank you for your work!'}, {'account_id': 23173, 'date': '2018-01-23 13:32:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Hi Martin, 

Code looks good to me but I don't see the documentation update. 
Can you add it before we merge ?"}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-23 14:21:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-23 14:22:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

Hi Maxime! Thanks for reviewing my code! I added a paragraph about unit conversion and new fields. Thanks you!'}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-23 14:29:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

(6 comments)'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-23 14:36:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-23 14:41:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Hi Luka! Thanks again for reviewing this code.
I shifted lines with more than 79 chars and I switched the 's' from 'formula' to 'includes'.
But in English, information is invariable and so, does not need any 's'. But as a french guy too, I understand the struggle well ;D
Thanks you again"}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-23 14:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-23 16:28:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 23173, 'date': '2018-01-24 08:47:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

@Martin

the radosgw collection in ceilometer collector is not good (cf comment). Since the collector is not deprecated already, you need to update it before we can merge the patch.

thx'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-24 10:19:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-24 10:26:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Hi @Maxime! Thanks you for telling me that I missed it. I just added the new conversion process for radosgw too!'}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-24 13:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

(1 comment)

Hi martin, I think you forgot a line. Documentation looks good, thanks!'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-24 16:36:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-24 17:03:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Some get_* functions are still missing unit conversion.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-24 17:27:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 26767, 'date': '2018-01-24 17:33:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

Hi @Luka! I added a unit conversion for the volume metrics. You are right, even if there is no current conversion done for this, we should allow the users and operators to do so.
Nevertheless, I didn't added it in the except part of the code as you suggested, but in the try block, so new yaml configuration file users could eventually use an unit conversion, but former method users will still have the same unchanged behavior.
Thanks you again for you reviews :)"}, {'account_id': 23060, 'date': '2018-01-25 21:54:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2018-01-26 05:46:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Workflow+1'}]

commit_message:
Manage metrics units in yaml configuration.

Allow users and operators to control the conversions units,
by filling source and destinations units for the metrics.
Differents units can now be affected to metrics from a same resource.

Task: 6077
Story: 2001396

Change-Id: I79713063d530737df20d4d910afc7c7e489aa2c5

commit_message:
Consume blacklisted_ip_addresses in workflows

The ceph-ansible and skydive workflows now consumes the
blacklisted_ip_addresses input.

The enable_ssh_admin workflow is modified to consume a list of
ip addresses and only enable ssh on the given set of addresses.

Change-Id: I4255739c852409fb8e170a9913fe7ad810711734
Depends-On: Ic158171c629e82892e480f1e6903a67457f86064
Closes-Bug: #1743046
(cherry picked from commit f98c136078b356446362bf7506bcd708b14473cd)

[{'created': '2018-01-25 03:37:17.000000000', 'message': 'Allow a combination of labels for tag discover

Some downstream build pipelines do not apply a label which exactly
matches the version tag. The only way to build the full versioned tag
is by combining multiple labels in a template pattern.

Change-Id: Id0fb010ebcdd4d3f3650c94065fc42489475c42c

'}]
commit_message:
Allow a combination of labels for tag discover

Some downstream build pipelines do not apply a label which exactly
matches the version tag. The only way to build the full versioned tag
is by combining multiple labels in a template pattern.

This change uses a python string.format syntax to allow multiple tags
to be combined.

Change-Id: Id0fb010ebcdd4d3f3650c94065fc42489475c42c
Closes-Bug: #1743883

commit_message:
Collect most of var/lib/heat-config directory.

This add the heat agent notifications, and ensure we dont miss any
new agent (heat-config-docker-cmd).

It include the deployed/<hash>.json as it contains information about
the resource that triggered the script.

Change-Id: I20a73f1ca761873b6897f32c07eec377d3769a79

commit_message:
Maintenance task: Ordering resources by type

When fixing the creation or update of a resource, it's better to sort it
by its type starting with the root resources and leaving the leaf ones
at the end. For example, in case a network and a port failed to be
created, if the maintenance thread tries to create the port prior to
creating the network it will fail.

The same could happens to deletion, it's preferable to delete the leaf
resources prior to deleting the root ones to avoid any conflict.

This patch is adding such sorting mechanism to the maintenance.py database
module that is used by the maintenance task when listing the resources
that needs to be fixed.

Change-Id: Ibc8312bf70b221626e389ea68bfa4c69f6a2cb67
Partial-Bug: #1605089

commit_message:
Indicating the location tests directory in oslo_debug_helper

According to [1], we can passing a "-t" argument to
oslo_debug_helper to indicate the directory where tests
are located. This will solves ImportError exception.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/oslotest/latest/user/features.html

Change-Id: I95f9acb111f210b87fe32aba301a7c56826e0e22

commit_message:
Add os-collect-config to requirements

The test that uses os-collect-config, ZaqarSignalTransportTest, is
staying in heat-tempest-plugin and being removed from
heat_integrationtests in the Heat tree. Add it to requirements here so
we can drop it from test-requirements there.

commit_message:
Include policy in tree for ease of deployment

Some deployment methods are using the files delivered by the
installation of packages to configure dashboards.
For example, it's possible to pip install heat-dashboard and
use the use local_settings.d files shipped inside the package
to deploy the heat-dashboard.

When the heat dashboard was not a plugin and included in horizon,
it was usable without having to care about the policy file.
This has changed, as the file is not shipped into horizon by
default, and is not available when pip installing the heat
dashboard directly, unlike the other files (above).

This patch follows the pattern set by murano here [1], to be
able to use the default policy file, shipped with the code,
after a pip install of the heat-dashboard.

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/murano-dashboard/blob/873fd7ff85f3695a9eab3c5b7269153989ea9f02/muranodashboard/conf/murano_policy.json

Change-Id: I7e1d74bebc97874c9049f6be33cef27806739b11

commit_message:
Allow data migrations to accept options

This allows migration to be tuned to a specific deployment. For example,
when we will migrate nodes to hardware types, an option will be used
to specify what to do with missing interfaces.

Change-Id: Ie5045b20b7420fc9b5d864bfb18258a4d8b93334
Related-Bug: #1690185

commit_message:
Move step 1 preparation to deploy-steps-tasks.yaml

This moves the writing of various files that are consumed by the
tasks in deploy-steps-tasks.yaml, hopefully this is clearer, and
it also means we can drive the creation of these files via ansible
directly using https://review.openstack.org/528354

Change-Id: I173d22ebcbc986cefdef47f81298abe10ce8591b

commit_message:
Add DefaultHeatEnvironments action

This action provides a mechanism to load a default_environments.yaml
file from the t-h-t templates which containers a 'default_environments'
array of Heat environments that will get appended to the plan
environments.

This is a useful mechanism for end users or downstream users who
wish to inject their own defaults into TripleO without having
to create large patches of Heat resource registry entries.

Change-Id: I55e20a19f311d8c4ad0ccf01260f18f983a91830
Closes-bug: #1745154

commit_message:
Fix upgrade order, align docs with script

When upgrading to Ocata, the check for galera changes in haproxy
so we need to deploy galera first then deploy haproxy second.

Fix the order in the run-upgrade.sh script.

Change-Id: I64ff9d5cfb5a6aec4fb793aaff11b4bb82e1aadb

commit_message:
Fix LBaaSv2 config and package requirements

The LBaaSv2 (not Octavia) requires the net-utils(tools) package to
function. Additionally the user_group needs to be set to an OS specific
value. This change adds a default allowing the user to override the new
option `neutron_lbaasv2_user_group` as needed but the default will be
inherited from the os specific variable file.

Change-Id: Ic4b9461e369f1db94dfcfc3cebae034b3d38bb09
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix router port creation

Now the port AFTER_UPDATE event is captured on the l3_ovn plugin,
and we make sure that it will succeed even if the router port
is still not created (which is a normal condition during initial
port create inside l3 because neutron router port creation
calls update before the flow continues to OVN L3 plugin, and
it's able to create the LRP).

Change-Id: I2a695ffc2ece23c9c3658511a9b2b03d4d3d15ef
Closes-Bug: 1745343

commit_message:
Fix some reST field lists in docstrings

Probably the most common format for documenting arguments is reST field
lists [1]. This change updates some docstrings to comply with the field
lists syntax.

commit_message:
Improve IPC and forking reliability in tests

These tests were randomly timing out in the CI:

  - JournalPeriodicProcessorTest.test_handle_sighup_gracefully
  - JournalPeriodicProcessorTest.test_reset_called_on_sighup

These failures are suspected to have been happening due to a race
condition between the test and the child process. This patch adds more
robustness to the way the pipe is used, refactors their code for better
maintainability and adds a forced delay to give time for the child
process to settle before starting to test.

Change-Id: I1a90963d1d30e8c03b2842fda8e1a77dd2c687fe

commit_message:
Implementation for UEFI iSCSI boot for ILO

This change adds new methods in management interface and enhance
boot interface of 'ilo' hardware type to support boot from iSCSI
volume in UEFI boot mode.

Change-Id: I585e0ef90f4397af1f09920c3a1bc47ddbcb1a97
Related-Bug: #1526861

commit_message:
Traits support

This adds support for the traits APIs in both the node portion of the
SDK, and the openstackclient plugin. We also bump the last known API
version to 1.37 to get access to the new API.

Change-Id: I72017d51dea194ec062a66cb19d718ba827e7427
Partial-Bug: #1722194
Depends-On: I313fa01fbf20bf0ff19f102ea63b02e72ac2b856

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-27 14:44:07.000000000', 'message': 'Ignore errors in OS::stack_id output

If a provider stack contained an OS::stack_id output and there was an error
in the output, we would raise TemplateOutputError when trying to calculate
the reference ID of the facade resource. Since we do that in many API
calls, such an error could render the stack effectively unusable.

If we encounter such an error, log it and fall back to the default
reference ID.

Change-Id: I1bc921fe74c54eb0999541ef36afc42b9c19e9bc
Partial-Bug: #1712280
Related-Bug: #1719333
(cherry picked from commit af0feeb18a4f5fb2c20fffb6d85617d1775e5844)
'}]
commit_message:
Ignore errors in OS::stack_id output

If a provider stack contained an OS::stack_id output and there was an error
in the output, we would raise TemplateOutputError when trying to calculate
the reference ID of the facade resource. Since we do that in many API
calls, such an error could render the stack effectively unusable.

If we encounter such an error, log it and fall back to the default
reference ID.

Change-Id: I1bc921fe74c54eb0999541ef36afc42b9c19e9bc
Partial-Bug: #1712280
Related-Bug: #1719333
(cherry picked from commit af0feeb18a4f5fb2c20fffb6d85617d1775e5844)

I've been testing this on stable/newton [1][2] and I saw the reproducer fail and the fix pass. Currently still waiting for results to post on those reviews because zuul got restarted a couple of times tonight, preventing results from posting to the reviews. I rechecked them again so we should get results posted soon.

I dug into why the bug doesn't reproduce on master and found that in newer os-brick, it retries _connect_single_volume in the event of a failure, does a cleanup that removes and disconnects devices, then tries the connect again [3]. We can see it in the logs on the reproducer test on master [5] where the connect fails first with "Could not find the WWN for sda." then disconnects things, then tries again and succeeds the second time.

Newer os-brick is tolerating the underlying bug, so I think we still need this nova change as the proper fix and not rely on os-brick's retry ability. If you take a look at the nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py code, neither _destroy nor _undefine_domain disconnect volumes. But then _get_guest_xml eventually goes to connect volumes. So we have a mismatch there which is wrong. We're inherently doing something wrong by trying to connect when there hasn't been a disconnect.

[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/512896

Matt, thanks for this investigation. It's not about to see the instance is ERROR state it's about that inside the guest to be not able to access to the mounted volume."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2017-10-18 08:45:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

Matt, the error is around compute host reboot, not instance reboot. This patch fixes instance reboot to correctly recover from a host reboot. The reproducer is:

* Create an instance with an encrypted volume
* Reboot the compute host
* Ensure the instance restarts after compute host reboot
* Note that the instance's volume is not decrypted

After the compute host reboot there are obviously no attachments. Instance recovery after the compute host reboot happens during _hard_reboot. A side-effect of _get_guest_xml is that it will connect volumes. This is a historic bug from 2011 (see previous review comments), but one which the calling code now relies on. So now the instance has volumes attached, but not encryptors. We pass reboot=True to _create_domain_and_network, which explicitly prevents encryptors from being attached. When the instance boots, the volume is still encrypted.

We fix this by not passing reboot=True to _create_domain_and_network during hard reboot, and therefore allowing encryptors to be re-attached. The problem with this is that if the compute host hasn't been rebooted, encryptors will still be attached and this fails. We fix this second problem by forcing hard reboot to tear down volumes first so it's always starting fresh whether the compute host has just rebooted or not. This succeeds in all cases. It also aligns with the existing intention to have reboot be a 'try to fix all the things' option for users so an operator doesn't have to log in to a compute host to fix things manually. IOW we should really have been doing this anyway, and it also fixes this bug.

A complete fix for this bug would involve removing side-effects from _get_guest_xml, and updating callers to do any required configuration explicitly, which will involve inferring what that required configuration is. We should also ensure that volume and encryptor attach always happen together, wherever that is. These changes will come with a much higher risk of regressions, though, and they won't be backportable."}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2017-10-18 09:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 10135, 'date': '2017-10-20 11:20:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

(3 comments)

Thanks for the reviews and apologies for the delay here.

bug #1724573 is an additional use case I was also attempting to resolve with this change given bug #1597234 is no longer reproducible against master. Unfortunately this isn't enough to fix bug #1724573 as we can't call the Cinder API with the empty admin context provided by init_host when using resume_guests_state_on_host_boot.

For now I'm going to propose a new change to initially skip any attempt to restart instances with encrypted volumes when resume_guests_state_on_host_boot is enabled. This should allow users to manually restart their instances after n-cpu host reboots without the instances booting while pointing to the still encrypted volume data.

We can then look at copying the approach taken by Neutron in the _heal_instance_info_cache periodic job where we use raw credentials from nova.conf in order to talk to the Neutron API with an empty admin context.

I'd also like to stash the encryption metadata in the BDM when using front-end (compute host) encryptors as this metadata shouldn't change for the lifecycle of the volume AFAIK.

-W'ing this change for now, I'd still like us to do this but resolving bug #1724573 is my current priority."}, {'account_id': 10135, 'date': '2017-10-20 16:08:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 10135, 'date': '2017-10-20 17:10:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

[{'created': '2016-11-21 19:31:29.000000000', 'message': 'WIP libvirt: Reconnect volumes and encryptors during a hard reboot

Closes-bug#1597234
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986
'}, {'created': '2016-11-22 14:23:49.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Reconnect volumes and encryptors during a hard reboot

The libvirt driver would previously leave volumes connected and
encryptors attached on a host during a hard reboot of an instance before
recreating the domain XML via _get_guest_xml. This eventually calls
connect_volume for each volume, however as the encryptors are still
attached the relevant devtmpfs paths may no longer be present.

To avoid this the libvirt driver now uses the full destroy method to
both remove the domain, detach any encryptors and finally disconnect
volumes. This allows _get_guest_xml to correctly reconnect said volumes
and reattach the encryptors when recreating the domain.

Closes-bug: #1597234
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986
'}, {'created': '2016-11-22 16:40:29.000000000', 'message': 'WIP libvirt: Reconnect volumes and encryptors during a hard reboot

Closes-bug#1597234
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986
'}, {'created': '2016-11-22 16:55:56.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Reconnect volumes and encryptors during a hard reboot

When hard rebooting an instance the Libvirt driver would previously
leave volumes connected and encryptors attached on the host. This could
lead to failures when recreating the domain as Nova attempts to connect
to volumes that are already connected and have encryptors attached.

To avoid this a full destroy is now called for when hard rebooting an
instance. This detaches any encryptors and disconnects the volumes from
the host allowing the volumes to be reconnected and encryptors
reattached when the instance is redefined.

Closes-bug: #1597234
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986

'}, {'created': '2017-10-12 12:42:52.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Fully destroy instances during a hard reboot

Previously the Libvirt driver would only call _destroy and
_undefine_domain when hard rebooting an instance. This would leave
vifs, volumes and any associated encryptors present on the host.

When using encrypted volumes this can lead to failures when the instance
is then recreated, calling down into _get_guest_xml and
_get_guest_storage_config and eventually connect_volume. With the
encryptor attached this call will fail for most backends as the original
path to the volume is now used to present the unencrypted device to the
instance.

Additionally, when using the same encryptors and
resume_state_on_host_boot to restart instances after a host
reboot the skipping of any logic associated with attaching the
encryptors will leave the unencrypted volume attached.

To correct both of these issues _hard_reboot now calls destroy to
disconnect volume and detach encryptors. The reboot parameter is also
dropped from the eventual call to _create_domain_and_network to ensure
these are reconnected and attached prior to the instance being
restarted.

Closes-bug: #1597234
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986
'}, {'created': '2017-10-20 16:08:39.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Fully destroy instances during _hard_reboot

The Libvirt driver would previously only call _destroy and
_undefine_domain when hard rebooting an instance. This would leave vifs
plugged, volumes connected and encryptors attached on the host.

However _hard_reboot is also used to simply start instances. If used
after a host reboot on an instance with encrypted volumes _hard_reboot
will make no attempt to reattach the required encryptors leaving the
fully encrypted volume attached to the instance.

This change corrects this by calling for a full destroy of the instance
during a _hard_reboot before ensuring vifs are plugged and encryptors
attached in the resulting call to _create_domain_and_network.

Closes-bug: #1724573
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986
'}, {'created': '2017-11-22 15:24:22.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Re-initialise volumes, encryptors, and vifs on hard reboot

We call _hard_reboot during reboot, power_on, and
resume_state_on_host_boot. It functions essentially by tearing as much
of an instance as possible before recreating it, which additionally
makes it useful to operators for attempting automated recovery of
instances in an inconsistent state.

The Libvirt driver would previously only call _destroy and
_undefine_domain when hard rebooting an instance. This would leave vifs
plugged, volumes connected, and encryptors attached on the host. It
also means that when we try to restart the instance, we assume all
these things are correctly configured. If they are not, the instance
may fail to start at all, or may be incorrectly configured when
starting.

For example, consider an instance with an encrypted volume after a
compute host reboot. When we attempt to start the instance, power_on
will call _hard_reboot. The volume will be coincidentally re-attached
as a side-effect of calling _get_guest_xml(!), but when we call
_create_domain_and_network we pass reboot=True, which tells it not to
reattach the encryptor, as it is assumed to be already attached. We
are therefore left presenting the encrypted volume data directly to
the instance without decryption.

The approach in this patch is to ensure we recreate the instance as
fully as possible during hard reboot. This means not passing
vifs_already_plugged and reboot to _create_domain_and_network, which
in turn requires that we fully destroy the instance first. This
addresses the specific problem given in the example, but also a whole
class of potential volume and vif related issues of inconsistent
state.

Because we now always tear down volumes, encryptors, and vifs, we are
relying on the tear down of these things to be idempotent.  This
highlighted that detach of the luks and cryptsetup encryptors were not
idempotent. We depend on the fixes for those os-brick drivers.

Depends-On: I31d72357c89db53a147c2d986a28c9c6870efad0
Depends-On: I9f52f89b8466d03699cfd5c0e32c672c934cd6fb

Closes-bug: #1724573
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986

commit_message:
libvirt: Re-initialise volumes, encryptors, and vifs on hard reboot

We call _hard_reboot during reboot, power_on, and
resume_state_on_host_boot. It functions essentially by tearing as much
of an instance as possible before recreating it, which additionally
makes it useful to operators for attempting automated recovery of
instances in an inconsistent state.

The Libvirt driver would previously only call _destroy and
_undefine_domain when hard rebooting an instance. This would leave vifs
plugged, volumes connected, and encryptors attached on the host. It
also means that when we try to restart the instance, we assume all
these things are correctly configured. If they are not, the instance
may fail to start at all, or may be incorrectly configured when
starting.

For example, consider an instance with an encrypted volume after a
compute host reboot. When we attempt to start the instance, power_on
will call _hard_reboot. The volume will be coincidentally re-attached
as a side-effect of calling _get_guest_xml(!), but when we call
_create_domain_and_network we pass reboot=True, which tells it not to
reattach the encryptor, as it is assumed to be already attached. We
are therefore left presenting the encrypted volume data directly to
the instance without decryption.

The approach in this patch is to ensure we recreate the instance as
fully as possible during hard reboot. This means not passing
vifs_already_plugged and reboot to _create_domain_and_network, which
in turn requires that we fully destroy the instance first. This
addresses the specific problem given in the example, but also a whole
class of potential volume and vif related issues of inconsistent
state.

Because we now always tear down volumes, encryptors, and vifs, we are
relying on the tear down of these things to be idempotent.  This
highlighted that detach of the luks and cryptsetup encryptors were not
idempotent. We depend on the fixes for those os-brick drivers.

Depends-On: I31d72357c89db53a147c2d986a28c9c6870efad0
Depends-On: I9f52f89b8466d03699cfd5c0e32c672c934cd6fb

Closes-bug: #1724573
Change-Id: Id188d48609f3d22d14e16c7f6114291d547a8986

commit_message:
Remove name from project stanza

This is now optional, and should be discouraged in in-repo configs.

Additionally:
* Block 1.18 release of openstackdocstheme, it does not work with the
  sphinx version. This change is needed for building.
* Fix some references to use mitaka files

Change-Id: I692c4f2e38ad4acbecfe02d03068ea293b04077f

The error_handler_spec is supposed to be a dict of dict of dicts, but
we had it as a dict of dict of functions, for unknown (historical?)
reasons.

Fix that, so that errors which occur in the Sahara API, but are not
otherwise caught by `sahara.utils.api.Rest.route` get handled correctly
by Flask instead of leading to some arcane error far down the stack.

Closes-Bug: #1745236
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Flask error_handler_spec

The error_handler_spec is supposed to be a dict of dict of dicts, but
we had it as a dict of dict of functions, for unknown (historical?)
reasons.

Fix that, so that errors which occur in the Sahara API, but are not
otherwise caught by `sahara.utils.api.Rest.route` get handled correctly
by Flask instead of leading to some arcane error far down the stack.

Change-Id: I1e9d5f3fa00308baa7eee101c1f3b5a666cae4aa
Closes-Bug: #1745236

commit_message:
Dynamically add python version into launch_command

Ubuntu Xenial or later server won't install Python2 anymore by default.
Sahara should have the ability to dynamically edit the remotely executed
python script based on what python is available.

Change-Id: Ie0fdd829d1b0ff019329957fbdbbfd150320b8ab
Closes-Bug: #1739009

commit_message:
save logs for check jobs when they succeed

The default is to discard logs when a job succeeds, but we need the
logs for these jobs because they are reports that reviewers use to
evaluate the releases being proposed.

Change-Id: Ibba75a547bee5a8a5e7fba76b5962c0382009bb2
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Suppress subTest() expected errors

Prior to this patch, calling subTest from a test inside a class
that inherits from osc_lib.TestCase would have failed the test.
This failure is either due to lack of support prior to PY3.4 [1], or
long-standing bug in testtools repo [2] which TestCase inherits from.

The patch suppresses both errors, so to allow writing better tests
using subTest, despite the fact that it is currently broken.

[1] - https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.4.html#unittest
[2] - https://bugs.launchpad.net/testtools/+bug/1219404

Partial-Bug: #1742343

Change-Id: I56bb3501d7a33fcec4fd971b2d9685d113e0af43

subject: Handle TZ change in iso8601 >=0.1.12
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-25 21:22:06.000000000', 'message': 'Handle TZ change in iso8601 >=0.1.12

The iso8601 lib introduced a change such that if running on python
3.2 or later it internally uses the python timezone information
instead of its own implementation. This does not change direct
date handling, but when converting this value there is a slight
difference where now python 2.x will show UTC times as "UTC", but
on python 3 they will end up with "UTC+00:00".

The to_primitive call for DateTime fields was doing an exact match
on "UTC" to determine whether to include "Z" in the resulting string.
This updates that handling to recognize either of the new values.

Change-Id: I48329aa69abafc1d8efe2b38d7575261b8da916c
Closes-bug: #1744160
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>
'}]
commit_message:
Handle TZ change in iso8601 >=0.1.12

The iso8601 lib introduced a change such that if running on python
3.2 or later it internally uses the python timezone information
instead of its own implementation. This does not change direct
date handling, but when converting this value there is a slight
difference where now python 2.x will show UTC times as "UTC", but
on python 3 they will end up with "UTC+00:00".

The to_primitive call for DateTime fields was doing an exact match
on "UTC" to determine whether to include "Z" in the resulting string.
This updates that handling to recognize either of the new values.

Change-Id: I48329aa69abafc1d8efe2b38d7575261b8da916c
Closes-bug: #1744160
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>

commit_message:
OVN HA: Set the OVN Resource Agent parameter 'inactive_probe_interval'

This parameter is required to configure the inactive probe interval. If not
specified, this param defaults to 5 seconds which is not enough. This patch sets
the value of this param to 180 seconds.

Change-Id: Ifbfb2a1ced308e4e4c89f0db31808df17cb43e7e

commit_message:
Fix pip install failure

A pip install on the current repo state would fail, because
pip is trying to install files it can't find [1].

We should use the proper files directly, like the other
files given in the setup.cfg.

This also fixes the config generator configuration path, to
ensure it's generated to the right filename.

[1]: http://paste.openstack.org/show/653462/

Change-Id: If2866be977bc5b4bb5632f4eeb51cec1b638a46d

commit_message:
Stop spamming ansible/ansible

Having the system-required template in place means we're running
merge-check on all ansible patches - and reporting back the results.

We need to stop that.

Change-Id: I75f6086174eb8f64d82185a153a55641425c9632

commit_message:
Fix bad autospec usage

There is no autospec kwarg on mock.Mock or mock.MagicMock, yet
several places in our tests were trying to autospec using that.
Fixed to use mock.create_autospec instead.

May or may not want to subsequently use MockAutospecFixture
as added to oslotest by 0bde35899a10875891f0592961c01e9fbb854738
but that would be in a follow-on patch.

Change-Id: Ia7845a003f1827b36684a7be10c26d4d6d1741c0
Partial-Bug: #1735588

commit_message:
Use mock.patch to setup test objects

Previously we saved original values and replaced it with new values
in setUp() and restored the original values in tearDown().
This can be done in a safer and briefer way by using mock.patch
as mock.patch.stopall does this automatically.

This commit also converts most logics in tearDown() to addCleanup.
Items registered by addCleanup are called even if setUp fails
unlike tearDown, so it is much safer than tearDown.

Part of blueprint mock-framework-in-unit-tests
Change-Id: I37f62a3f288bcf54fdf225af7adb649ffe917487

commit_message:
Add a small sleep when trying to predict X-Timestamp

The existing test works fine if you're running the tests on an
all-in-one, but is pretty brittle if you aren't running them on the
one and only proxy-server they're hitting.

Add 0.1s sleep to allow *some* clock slippage between client and server.

Change-Id: Iacd08e9f703d08d0092b5e8eb53fe287ba1d1596

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-24 07:17:34.000000000', 'message': "Can not set portgroup mode as a number

When creating portgroup, mode accepts a string or a number, e.g.:
active-backup or 1.

While setting new mode for an existing portgroup will raise an error, if
the mode is passed as a number:

    # openstack --os-baremetal-api-version 1.26 baremetal port group \
    set c42f9bf8-3b5d-4673-b6c1-832c10e4fecf --mode 1
    Invalid input for field/attribute mode. Value: '1'. Wrong type. Expected
    '<type 'unicode'>', got '<type 'int'>' (HTTP 400)

This patch add quotes to mode string to avoid unwanted conversion.

Change-Id: I1bfe6d203c5420f06c8d7ead487250da1847e103
Closes-Bug: #1745099
"}]
commit_message:
Can not set portgroup mode as a number

When creating portgroup, mode accepts a string or a number, e.g.:
active-backup or 1.

While setting new mode for an existing portgroup will raise an error, if
the mode is passed as a number:

    # openstack --os-baremetal-api-version 1.26 baremetal port group \
    set c42f9bf8-3b5d-4673-b6c1-832c10e4fecf --mode 1
    Invalid input for field/attribute mode. Value: '1'. Wrong type. Expected
    '<type 'unicode'>', got '<type 'int'>' (HTTP 400)

This patch add quotes to mode string to avoid unwanted conversion.

Change-Id: I1bfe6d203c5420f06c8d7ead487250da1847e103
Closes-Bug: #1745099

commit_message:
Tweak Sahara to make version discovery easier

Or at least, tweak Sahara to be more accomodating to keystoneauth's way
of doing version discovery.

* Don't require auth to do version discovery
* Make project ID in URL optional for APIv1 (and also for APIv2, but
  don't go around advertising that... *wink*)

Change-Id: Idb6f734aee26cab5bd629963a66ba01c92760864
Closes-Bug: #1744350

Add the ability to extend npiv volumes

The compute host does not need to do anything for the client to
see the extended size.

If the option set to false, will the force deletion operation still works?'}, {'account_id': 23078, 'date': '2018-01-20 19:32:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Force deletion of clusters

* Add force delete operation to engine using stack abandon
* Basic unit tests for force delete
* Necessary removal of "direct engine" code
* Change schema of APIv2 cluster delete to allow force delete
* Unit tests for new cluster delete schema
* Basic docs about force delete
* Release note

bp sahara-force-delete
Partial-Bug: #1647411

Change-Id: Ida72677c0a4110cb78edf9d62d8330cd4608ff76

commit_message:
Fixes specifying OVSDB URIs with TLS for ODL OVS

This fixes an issue with enabling TLS and specifying the OVSDB URI
connection parameters for the ovs::opendaylight class.  The settings
were not being propogated into the OVS manager configuration when
specified in the class.

Closes-Bug: 1744967

Change-Id: I004cffed10401a0132368375f0377a7aa45b5401
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fixes VLAN trunk setting issue

When setting VLAN trunks, os-win's networkutils expects the
trunk_vlans key-value argument, but the trunk_driver passes
the vlan_trunk argument, which is wrong.

This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: Iabf845fefdbe564f2c8d7f5ac34e5e97cf480897
Closes-Bug: #1745362

commit_message:
Fixes ceph deploy gates

- Ceph images are not being built when using depends-on a kolla build
  job.
- Sync inventory files with current ones which causes ceph to fail due
  missing groups.
- Small corrections in ceph config.yml syntax.

- enable ceph nfs only when enable_ceph_nfs is true

commit_message:
Define test logging setting in openstack_auth

We see the following message when running openstack_auth UT.
This is due to no LOGGING definition in openstack_auth/test/settings.py.

  No handlers could be found for logger "openstack_auth.utils"

Change-Id: I8f00eea13d8672a76aee975196ddd6ff723c03a9

commit_message:
Create group from snapshot-group failure leaves behind the volume

While creating a group from snapshot group or source group, if the
quota exceeds during volume creation, the volume which are scheduled
for creation are left behind in the DB.Only Group gets destroyed from
the DB. To solve this, If error happens, taskflow will handle
rollback of quota and removal of volume entry in the db.

Change-Id: I5d60680fa92e50e51c9b3a6bcc940b18bef5b150
Closes-Bug: #1727314

commit_message:
ignore unofficial projects in latest.yaml

Update the template generator to ignore unofficial projects when
rendering for the current series. Ignoring, rather than throwing an
error, allows us to clean up the data without the build breaking.

To make the validation work for glance-store, a new field is needed to
set the 'deliverable-name', since it is different from the project
name used to build URLs.

Change-Id: I0876c93b49d57818d0b689fd03a0171a96e27547
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Remove name from project stanza

This is now optional, and should be discouraged in in-repo configs.

Additionally:
* Block 1.18 release of openstackdocstheme, it does not work with the
 sphinx version. This change is needed for building.
* Include file from proper branch - the file has been removed from
  master branch.

Change-Id: I692c4f2e38ad4acbecfe02d03068ea293b04077f
(cherry picked from commit 4434ba8c4bbb67ea8badf1a72b6db54398d9d6d4)

commit_message:
check APT_SOURCES earlier

Bug Description:
apt-sources only checks for an existing file after all the debootstrap
process, which can take a long time to finish. This check could be
move earlier in the chain.

In my opinion,it's unsafe to "move" this check earlier.But we can do
a check at the begin,this will fix this bug and keep the safety of the
program at the same time.

Also,change the test element in apt-sources to a more common situation.

Thanks for greghaynes's suggestion

Change-Id: I8a92f4d8ff75f802063c39af5fae99a1d4c829bc

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-04-27 13:54:05.000000000', 'message': 'Allow setting {provisioning,cleaning}_network in node driver_info

Now user can add the provisioning and cleaning networks in driver_info
of the node. The can update the network information using
" ironic node-update <node-uuid> add
driver_info/provisioning_network=3aea0de6-4b92-44da-9aa0-52d134c83f9c
driver_info/cleaning_network=3aea0de6-4b92-44da-9aa0-52d134c83fdf ".
If these network information is updated in the node, at the time of
provisioning the baremetal these network details are used, if these
network details are not updated in node, then ironic uses the default
network configuration details which are present in ironic.conf

Closes Bug: #1614876

Change-Id: I4caec34d85304fe887bcc28b7528cceceb3acfe8

commit_message:
Allow setting {provisioning,cleaning,rescuing}_network in driver_info

These values have priority over ones defined in ironic.conf. Also modify
validation code to only used network UUID cached on task.network if:
1. the requested XXX_network is UUID, not name
2. the requested XXX_network is the same as the cached one.

Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Tantsur <dtantsur@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1614876
Change-Id: I4caec34d85304fe887bcc28b7528cceceb3acfe8

commit_message:
Implement availability_zone_hints for networks and routers.

Adds an optional parameter to the create_network and
create_router-methods, for use with availability zone-scheduling of
network agents.

Change-Id: Ifb93a10415dc676f5cc56b5315f2dff24fc395b8

[{'created': '2018-01-24 21:58:12.000000000', 'message': 'Use xlarge flavor for undercloud nodes

Minimal requirements for undercloud nodes are described here:
https://images.rdoproject.org/docs/baremetal/requirements.html

Specifically, it says:

"The undercloud VM or baremetal machine requires: [...] 16 GB free
memory"

It's not just documentation that asks to change default flavor. If you
try to deploy using tripleo-quickstart in RDO cloud / OVB, you will hit
both tripleo-validations failures like:

There are 4 cores in the system, but there should be at least 8.
The RAM on the undercloud node is 7822 MB, the minimal recommended value
is 16384 MB.

And even when validations are ignored, the resulting environment fails
because mariadb (or another crucial service) is killed by oom-killer. I
personally experienced mariadb killed and as a result, heat-api
failing when listing stacks with ECONNREFUSED from db server, which
finally resulted in overcloud deployment failure.

xlarge is the smallest default flavor that provides 16gb ram, and so
this patch uses this flavor.

This is a counterpart change to:
https://github.com/cybertron/openstack-virtual-baremetal/pull/39

Change-Id: I85ee3f2f4d6283ae45484a850e374c81e70f1912
'}]
commit_message:
Use xlarge flavor for undercloud nodes

Minimal requirements for undercloud nodes are described here:
https://images.rdoproject.org/docs/baremetal/requirements.html

Specifically, it says:

"The undercloud VM or baremetal machine requires: [...] 16 GB free
memory"

It's not just documentation that asks to change default flavor. If you
try to deploy using tripleo-quickstart in RDO cloud / OVB, you will hit
both tripleo-validations failures like:

There are 4 cores in the system, but there should be at least 8.
The RAM on the undercloud node is 7822 MB, the minimal recommended value
is 16384 MB.

And even when validations are ignored, the resulting environment fails
because mariadb (or another crucial service) is killed by oom-killer. I
personally experienced mariadb killed and as a result, heat-api
failing when listing stacks with ECONNREFUSED from db server, which
finally resulted in overcloud deployment failure.

xlarge is the smallest default flavor that provides 16gb ram, and so
this patch uses this flavor.

This is a counterpart change to:
https://github.com/cybertron/openstack-virtual-baremetal/pull/39

Change-Id: I85ee3f2f4d6283ae45484a850e374c81e70f1912

commit_message:
APIv2 support in client

* Support of all APIv2 features carried from APIv1 ("feature parity")
* Minimum amount of docs to pass the gate
* Endpoint manipulation and version discovery handled by keystoneauth
* APIv2 feature: decommision of specific instances (doc change only)
* APIv2 feature: force delete (new method)

Unit tests will arrive in a future patch.

bp v2-api-experimental-impl

Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>
Change-Id: I32178439fe85cc6d5faf4ac2e33ae80c08619de5

[{'created': '2018-01-22 17:33:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes websocket disconnects with client

Websocket was configured with a socket timeout of 10 seconds which was
causing the SSL connection to close with timeout errors.  By not
specifying a timeout the client connection will remain open and the
socket is changed to blocking, which fixes the issue.

Closes-Bug: 1744759

Change-Id: I01f81befdd19d8ad914761c7013f10f2b5d69602
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>
'}, {'created': '2018-01-23 19:43:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes SSL websocket disconnects with client

Websocket was configured with a socket timeout of 10 seconds which was
causing the SSL connection to close with timeout errors. This is due to
an issue with the websocket-client library not catching an SSL timeout
error properly.  This patch adds a check for SSL time out in the event
it is not caught and presented as a WebSocketTimeoutException.

Under normal circumstances the websocket will read and issue a timeout
if no data was received on the socket over the duration of the timeout.
This happens quite often in the thread because ODL is only sends port
status updates on an event.  The thread should just continue to poll in
the event of a time out (no data received).

Closes-Bug: 1744759

Change-Id: I01f81befdd19d8ad914761c7013f10f2b5d69602
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fixes SSL websocket disconnects with client

Websocket was configured with a socket timeout of 10 seconds which was
causing the SSL connection to close with timeout errors. This is due to
an issue with the websocket-client library not catching an SSL timeout
error properly.  This patch adds a check for SSL time out in the event
it is not caught and presented as a WebSocketTimeoutException.

Under normal circumstances the websocket will read and issue a timeout
if no data was received on the socket over the duration of the timeout.
This happens quite often in the thread because ODL is only sends port
status updates on an event.  The thread should just continue to poll in
the event of a time out (no data received).

Closes-Bug: 1744759

Change-Id: I01f81befdd19d8ad914761c7013f10f2b5d69602
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Handle TZ change in iso8601 >=0.1.12

The iso8601 lib introduced a change such that if running on python
3.2 or later it internally uses the python timezone information
instead of its own implementation. This does not change direct
date handling, but when converting this value there is a slight
difference where now python 2.x will show UTC times as "UTC", but
on python 3 they will end up with "UTC+00:00".

The to_primitive call for DateTime fields was doing an exact match
on "UTC" to determine whether to include "Z" in the resulting string.
This updates that handling to recognize either of the new values.

Change-Id: I71b58e8fd8fee8a57ee275ff3e0b77f165eca836
Closes-bug: #1744160

commit_message:
More efficiently clean up OVS ports

Previously, running neutron_ovs_cleanup on an installation with
5000 ports would time out even after setting the timeout to 3
hours. The code would do a bridge and port "by name" lookup for
every port due to being based off the ovs-vsctl implementation
where names are how everything is looked up. With this change,
the same test runs in ~1.5 mins.

This implementation adds a new OVSDB command that just looks up
the bridge, iterates over its ports, and deletes the ones that
should be deleted in a single transaction per bridge.

Change-Id: I23c81813654596d61d8d930e0bfb0f016f91bc46

commit_message:
Add support for Couchbase cluster provisioning

Implement cluster calls for Couchbase >= 3.0

When the change for couchbase allowing multiple types on
cluster-grow was added, the mongodb code was changed
to support possibly receiving a list.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I40cc15fa5fd3c12a789e1656ddbba83e4fec6b95
Co-Authored-By: Petr Malik <pmalik@tesora.com>
Co-Authored-By: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>
Implements: blueprint couchbase-cluster-support

subject: Allow defaults for Image/Flavor/RoleParameters in roles_data.yaml
messages: [{'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2018-01-24 02:34:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked from branch master.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2018-01-25 14:53:03.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned\n\nbackport not needed now.'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-24 02:34:13.000000000', 'message': 'Allow defaults for Image/Flavor/RoleParameters in roles_data.yaml

This allows specific roles, e.g ComputeRealTime to specify defaults
where the services are the same as some existing roles but a different
image and/or configuration are needed.

Inspired by discussion of this requirement in:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/531739/

RoleParametersDefaults is merged with the user provided parameters
with precendence to user parameters, as this is a special parameter,
which contains a map of the actual parameters to be applied to a
role.

Partially Implements: blueprint tripleo-realtime
Change-Id: I6497144340d3b9276e6ed141d3bc655bfbbeb53c
(cherry picked from commit d00671142620f06c23601be8e5de63df71afdfb4)

commit_message:
Allow defaults for Image/Flavor/RoleParameters in roles_data.yaml

This allows specific roles, e.g ComputeRealTime to specify defaults
where the services are the same as some existing roles but a different
image and/or configuration are needed.

Inspired by discussion of this requirement in:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/531739/

RoleParametersDefaults is merged with the user provided parameters
with precendence to user parameters, as this is a special parameter,
which contains a map of the actual parameters to be applied to a
role.

Partially Implements: blueprint tripleo-realtime
Change-Id: I6497144340d3b9276e6ed141d3bc655bfbbeb53c
(cherry picked from commit d00671142620f06c23601be8e5de63df71afdfb4)

commit_message:
Block construct >2.8.21

the release 2.8.22 of 'construct' lib has introduced a breaking change
to Python API wrt to available exceptions (see Issue #453 in construct),
which broke ironic-instpector and currently blocks its CI.

The only openstack project seeming to depend on construct
is ironic-inspector, and it has plans to drop this dependency.

To fix the CI in the meantime, this patch reverts the u-c for construct
to 2.8.21, and modifies the g-r accordingly.

Change-Id: I5c63c7f0b5d3122c0738d8591352f580185bd0d6

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE Trunks panel: delay loading data

This change helps to work with (eg. manually test) its parent change.
It intentionally slows down a few neutron API requests (by repeating
them N times and throwing away the first N-1 responses) so you have
the chance to experiment with how the UI looks before the API response
arrives. That way you can also see how the UI changes when the data
becomes available.

You can tune the slowdown by repeating the API calls different times.

Change-Id: I69001bd83d5187f23fd670cc85ff1ccf84b6cea7

commit_message:
tests: Use mock autospec in unit tests

Autospecing will ensure that the method signatures are respected
during calls.

oslotest.mock_fixture contains 2 components, one of them adds the autospec
argument to mock.Mock and mock.MagicMock, while the other one fixes the
autospec behaviour for mock.patch functions, and sets autospec to True by
default, unless otherwise specified.

Change-Id: Ib785be16e2b81a32dff32b0e070e34e0675d4b4f
Closes-Bug: #1735588

[{'created': '2018-01-19 17:00:53.000000000', 'message': "Update Block Storage Checklist

The castellan key management interface has
recently deprecated the 'api_class' configuration
option in favor of the 'backend' configuration

commit_message:
Add openshift masters to nodes

According to OpenShift's docs, the master nodes should be added to the
nodes list for them to be added as a node in the cluster and be part of
the openshift SDN. We are adding them as unschedulable for now so that
no PODs will be scheduled on the node.

https://docs.openshift.com/enterprise/3.1/install_config/install/advanced_install.html#marking-masters-as-unschedulable-nodes

Change-Id: I7ee862610cef161ca04e4f7d7ed6963c6c09bc14

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-12-20 20:10:06.000000000', 'message': 'Fix failure of UI validation in some shells

The Bourne shell, dash shell and other truly POSIX compliant shells
have no mechanism for `set -o pipefail`, thus causing a failure and
termination of deployment steps when being run from those systems.

In particular, Debian and Ubuntu systems see these failures.

In this particular use case, fortunately, the pipe to tee is not
truly necessary, when a simple redirection will suffice.

This patch proposes altering the pipe to a regular redirection in
a manner which will work across most if not all POSIX compliant
Linux systems.

Change-Id: Id52fbbca51a2491346ff979433387c7e695bbb43
Closes-Bug: 1739428
'}, {'created': '2018-01-18 00:14:13.000000000', 'message': 'Fix failure of UI validation in some shells

The Bourne shell, dash shell and other truly POSIX compliant shells
have no mechanism for `set -o pipefail`, thus causing a failure and
termination of deployment steps when being run from those systems.

In particular, Debian and Ubuntu systems see these failures.

This patch explicitly specifies the bash shell, meaning Debian and
Ubuntu systems will not trip up in running this script.

Change-Id: Id52fbbca51a2491346ff979433387c7e695bbb43
Closes-Bug: 1739428
'}]
commit_message:
Fix failure of UI validation in some shells

The Bourne shell, dash shell and other truly POSIX compliant shells
have no mechanism for `set -o pipefail`, thus causing a failure and
termination of deployment steps when being run from those systems.

In particular, Debian and Ubuntu systems see these failures.

This patch explicitly specifies the bash shell, meaning Debian and
Ubuntu systems will not trip up in running this script.

Change-Id: Id52fbbca51a2491346ff979433387c7e695bbb43
Closes-Bug: 1739428

commit_message:
bagpipe ML2: remove the route_target type driver

This change scraps the route_target type driver, in favor
of simply using bagpipe ML2 mechanism driver with the vxlan type
driver.

The route_target type driver required using a different main()
for the agent, which wasn't clean. It had no particular advantage
and required more code.

Co-Author: Corinne SAINT JALME <corinne.saintjalme@orange.com>
Change-Id: I5c46af4cb48e1ce0e5edd8831c8725bca711fb79

commit_message:
Consume requires-floating-ip from os-client-config

We added a flag to os-client-config to honor the 'requires-floating-ip'
setting in clouds.yaml. Use it to allow people to turn off floating ips
for auto_ip behavior in config.

Change-Id: I493beb66337eacb70361921bef835540465d1ccc

commit_message:
Add VolumeEncryptionTest to skip list

This test is failing when trying to clean up, because the volume
is still in use. There is a bug open to address the actual issue,
but we should skip the test in the meantime to not block promotion.

Change-Id: I2f58b28552e20352ee69efbc9cbac52d5da7c4f4
Related-Bug: 1744151

This is meant for backporting to pike, since in that version, swift

Change-Id: I403868e36000abd10be756dcbdb4ce32700f3fec

commit_message:
Configure auth_uri for swift proxy explicitly without suffix

This is meant for backporting to pike, since in that version, swift
proxy is the only service left that's configured with keystone v2.0.
This fixes that.

Change-Id: I403868e36000abd10be756dcbdb4ce32700f3fec
Closes-Bug: #1742654
(cherry picked from commit b9870d4c6cf1ca2e77dcfc7ca4855a8dde7ff5a6)
